# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: austrian-standards-international
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:austrian-standards-international/american-national-standards-institute] The **American National Standards Institute** (**ANSI**) is a private nonprofit organization that oversees the development of voluntary consensus standards for products, services, processes, systems, and personnel in the United States.
[src:austrian-standards-international/american-national-standards-institute] The organization also coordinates U.S. standards with international standards so that American products can be used worldwide.
[src:austrian-standards-international/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI accredits standards that are developed by representatives of other standards organizations, government agencies, consumer groups, companies, and others.
[src:austrian-standards-international/american-national-standards-institute] These standards ensure that the characteristics and performance of products are consistent, that people use the same definitions and terms, and that products are tested the same way.
[src:austrian-standards-international/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI also accredits standards developing organizations (SDOs) and provides a searchable directory of accredited standards developers (ASDs).
[src:austrian-standards-international/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI similarly accredits organizations that carry out product or personnel certification in accordance with requirements defined in international standards.
[src:austrian-standards-international/american-national-standards-institute] The organization's headquarters are in Washington, D.C.
[src:austrian-standards-international/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI's operations office is located in New York City.
[src:austrian-standards-international/american-national-standards-institute] The ANSI annual operating budget is funded by the sale of publications, membership dues and fees, accreditation services, fee-based programs, and international standards programs.
[src:austrian-standards-international/american-national-standards-institute] Many ANSI regulations are incorporated by reference into United States federal statutes (i.e. by OSHA regulations referring to individual ANSI specifications).
[src:austrian-standards-international/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI does not make these standards publicly available, and charges money for access to these documents; it further claims that it is copyright infringement for them to be provided to the public by others free of charge.
[src:austrian-standards-international/american-national-standards-institute] These assertions have been the subject of criticism and litigation.
[src:austrian-standards-international/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI was most likely formed in 1918, when five engineering societies and three government agencies founded the **American Engineering Standards Committee** (**AESC**).
[src:austrian-standards-international/american-national-standards-institute] In 1928, the AESC became the **American Standards Association** (**ASA**).
[src:austrian-standards-international/american-national-standards-institute] In 1966, the ASA was reorganized and became the **United States of America Standards Institute** (**USASI**).
[src:austrian-standards-international/american-national-standards-institute] In February 1969, Ralph Nader harshly criticized the USASI in public remarks as "manifestly deceptive" in several different ways.
[src:austrian-standards-international/american-national-standards-institute] He specifically attacked the name USASI as improperly implying some kind of official connection with the federal government of the United States.
[src:austrian-standards-international/american-national-standards-institute] had been members of the United Engineering Society (UES).
[src:austrian-standards-international/american-national-standards-institute] At the behest of the AIEE, they invited the U.S. government Departments of War, Navy (combined in 1947 to become the Department of Defense or DOD) and Commerce to join in founding a national standards organization.
[src:austrian-standards-international/american-national-standards-institute] According to Adam Stanton, the first permanent secretary and head of staff in 1919, AESC started as an ambitious program and little else.
[src:austrian-standards-international/american-national-standards-institute] Staff for the first year consisted of one executive, Clifford B.
[src:austrian-standards-international/american-national-standards-institute] LePage, who was on loan from a founding member, ASME.
[src:austrian-standards-international/american-national-standards-institute] An annual budget of $7,500 was provided by the founding bodies.
[src:austrian-standards-international/american-national-standards-institute] In 1931, the organization (renamed ASA in 1928) became affiliated with the U.S.
[src:austrian-standards-international/american-national-standards-institute] National Committee of the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC), which had been formed in 1904 to develop electrical and electronics standards.
[src:austrian-standards-international/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI's members are government agencies, organizations, academic and international bodies, and individuals.
[src:austrian-standards-international/american-national-standards-institute] In total, the Institute represents the interests of more than 270,000 companies and organizations and 30 million professionals worldwide.
[src:austrian-standards-international/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI's market-driven, decentralized approach has been criticized in comparison with more planned and organized international approaches to standardization.
[src:austrian-standards-international/american-national-standards-institute] Although ANSI itself does not develop standards, the Institute oversees the development and use of standards by accrediting the procedures of standards developing organizations.
[src:austrian-standards-international/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI accreditation signifies that the procedures used by standards developing organizations meet the institute's requirements for openness, balance, consensus, and due process.
[src:austrian-standards-international/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI also designates specific standards as American National Standards, or ANS, when the Institute determines that the standards were developed in an environment that is equitable, accessible and responsive to the requirements of various stakeholders.
[src:austrian-standards-international/american-national-standards-institute] Voluntary consensus standards quicken the market acceptance of products while making clear how to improve the safety of those products for the protection of consumers.
[src:austrian-standards-international/american-national-standards-institute] There are approximately 9,500 American National Standards that carry the ANSI designation.
[src:austrian-standards-international/american-national-standards-institute] The institute is the official U.S. representative to the two major international standards organizations, the International Organization for Standardization (ISO), as a founding member, and the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC), via the U.S.
[src:austrian-standards-international/american-national-standards-institute] ANSI participates in almost the entire technical program of both the ISO and the IEC, and administers many key committees and subgroups.
[src:austrian-standards-international/american-national-standards-institute] In many instances, U.S. standards are taken forward to ISO and IEC, through ANSI or the USNC, where they are adopted in whole or in part as international standards.
[src:austrian-standards-international/american-national-standards-institute] Adoption of ISO and IEC standards as American standards increased from 0.2% in 1986 to 15.5% in May 2012.
[src:austrian-standards-international/american-national-standards-institute] Each of the panels works to identify, coordinate, and harmonize voluntary standards relevant to these areas.
[src:austrian-standards-international/american-national-standards-institute] In 2009, ANSI and the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) formed the Nuclear Energy Standards Coordination Collaborative (NESCC).
[src:austrian-standards-international/american-national-standards-institute] NESCC is a joint initiative to identify and respond to the current need for standards in the nuclear industry.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] 'joining' or 'connection'), also known as the ***Anschluß Österreichs*** (pronunciationⓘ, English: Annexation of Austria), was the annexation of the Federal State of Austria into Nazi Germany on 12 March 1938.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] The idea of an *Anschluss* (a united Austria and Germany that would form a "Greater Germany") arose after the 1871 unification of Germany excluded Austria and the German Austrians from the Prussian-dominated German Empire.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] It gained support after the Austro-Hungarian Empire fell in 1918.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] This left Austria without most of the territories it had ruled for centuries and amid economic crisis.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] By the 1920s, the *Anschluss* proposal had strong support in both Austria and Germany, particularly to many Austrian citizens of the political left and center.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] One vehement supporter was prominent Social Democrat leader Otto Bauer, who served as the Austrian foreign minister in 1918–1919.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Support for unification with Germany came mainly from the belief that Austria, stripped of its imperial land, was not viable economically.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Popular support for the unification faded with time, although it remained as a concept in the contemporary Austrian political discourse.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] On 30 January 1933, Nazi Party leader Adolf Hitler was appointed chancellor of Germany.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Nazi Germany's agents cultivated pro-unification tendencies in Austria, and sought to undermine the Austrian government, which was controlled by the Fatherland Front, which opposed unification.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] During an attempted coup in July 1934, Austrian chancellor Engelbert Dollfuss was assassinated by Austrian Nazis.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] The defeat of the coup prompted many leading Austrian Nazis to go into exile in Germany, where they continued their efforts to unify the two countries.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] On 5 November 1937, Hitler informed his military aides that he would annex Austria and Czechoslovakia to the German Reich, and forced a meeting with Austrian chancellor Kurt Schuschnigg.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Although Schuschnigg viewed Austria as a "German State," he fiercely opposed annexation into the Greater Germanic Reich.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] His commitment to Austrian sovereignty was pushed to the brink on February 12, 1938, during a tense meeting with Adolf Hitler at Berchtesgaden.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Under the threat of military invasion, Schuschnigg accepted a devastating ultimatum: either appoint Arthur Seyss-Inquart, a prominent Austrian National Socialist, as Minister of the Interior and Security or face dire consequences.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] On the eve of 9 March 1938, Schuschnigg defiantly announced that there would be a referendum held on 13 March to decide between a possible union with Germany or the maintenance of Austria's sovereignty.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Schuschnigg expected to win a clear majority to face the Nazi challenge, but on 11 March, Hitler, again under the threat of German occupation, issued a demand for cancellation of the referendum and Schussnigg's immediate resignation.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Bowing to pressure and unrest from both German and Austrian Nazi factions, Schussnigg resigned, forcing Austrian president Wilhelm Miklas to reluctantly appoint Seyss-Inquart as Schussnigg's successor.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Within hours of taking office, Seyss-Inquart then "invited" Hitler and the German Army to cross the border to "restore order" in Austria on 12 March, unopposed by the Austrian military.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] A plebiscite was held on 10 April, resulting in 99.7% approval.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] The idea of grouping all Germans into one nation-state had been the subject of debate in the 19th century from the dissolution of the Holy Roman Empire in 1806 until the break-up of the German Confederation in 1866.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Austria had wanted a *Großdeutsche Lösung* (greater Germany solution), whereby the German states would unite under the leadership of the Austrian House of Habsburg.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] This solution would have included all the German states (including the non-German regions of Austria), but Prussia would have had to accept a secondary role.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] This controversy, called dualism, dominated Prusso-Austrian diplomacy and the politics of the German states in the mid-nineteenth century.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] In 1866 the feud finally came to an end during the Austro-Prussian War in which the Prussians defeated the Austrians and thereby excluded the Austrian Empire and German Austrians from Germany.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] The Prussian statesman Otto von Bismarck formed the North German Confederation, which included most of the remaining German states, aside from a few in the southwestern region of the German-inhabited lands, and further expanded the power of the Kingdom of Prussia.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Bismarck used the Franco-Prussian War (1870–1871) as a way to convince southwestern German states, including the Kingdom of Bavaria, to side with Prussia against the Second French Empire.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Due to Prussia's quick victory, the debate was settled and in 1871 the "*Kleindeutsch*" German Empire based on the leadership of Bismarck and Prussia formed—this excluded Austria.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Besides ensuring Prussian domination of a united Germany, the exclusion of Austria also ensured that Germany would have a substantial Protestant majority.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] The Austro-Hungarian Compromise of 1867, the *Ausgleich*, provided for a dual sovereignty, the Austrian Empire and the Kingdom of Hungary, under Franz Joseph I.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] This diverse empire included various different ethnic groups including Hungarians, Slavic ethnic groups such as Bosniaks, Croats, Czechs, Poles, Rusyns, Serbs, Slovaks, Slovenes, and Ukrainians, as well as Italians and Romanians ruled by a German minority.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] The empire caused tensions between the various ethnic groups.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Many Austrian pan-Germans showed loyalty to Otto von Bismarck and only to Germany, wore symbols that were temporarily banned in Austrian schools and advocated the dissolution of the empire to allow Austria to rejoin Germany, as it had been during the German Confederation of 1815–1866.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Although many Austrians supported pan-Germanism, many others still showed allegiance to the Habsburg monarchy and wished for Austria to remain an independent country.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Erich Ludendorff wrote to the Federal Foreign Office on 14 October 1918 about the possibility of conducting an Anschluss with the German areas of Austria-Hungary as its dissolution removed the problem of the country's numerous ethnic groups.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Secretary Wilhelm Solf opposed the proposal, stating that it "would provide the Entente with justification for demanding territorial compensations".
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Elite and popular opinion in the rump Republic of German-Austria after 1918 largely favored some sort of union with Germany.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] An Austrian provisional national assembly drafted a provisional constitution that stated that "German Austria is a democratic republic" (Article 1) and "German Austria is a component of the German Republic" (Article 2).
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Later plebiscites in the Austrian border provinces of Tyrol and Salzburg yielded majorities of 98% and 99% in favor of a unification with the Weimar Republic.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Further plebiscites were then forbidden.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Hugo Preuss, the drafter of the German Weimar Constitution, criticized efforts to prevent an Anschluss; he saw the prohibition as a contradiction of the Wilsonian principle of self-determination of peoples.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] The constitutions of the Weimar Republic and the First Austrian Republic both included the political goal of unification, which parties widely supported.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] In the early 1930s, the Austrian government looked to a possible customs union with the German Republic in 1931.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] However, ultimately regional patriotism was stronger than pan-German sentiment.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] In the Austrian Empire, each Kronland had its own functional government and enjoyed a fair amount of autonomy from Vienna, with "each looking to their own capital" instead.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Poincarés third government attempted to prevent an Anschluss by incorporating Austria into a Danubian Confederation in 1927.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] German Minister of Foreign Affairs Gustav Stresemann opposed it, as he saw it as an attempt to re-form the Austro-Hungarian Empire and offered to form a customs union with Austria.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Austrian Chancellor Ignaz Seipel, an Anschluss opponent, rejected the offer.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] In September 1929, Seipel was replaced by Johannes Schober, who pursued a pro-Germany policy and attempted to form a customs union.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] A political and economical crisis led to Schober losing power (30 September 1930) and Seipel returning to the government as Minister of Foreign Affairs.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Negotiations were restarted after Otto Ender became chancellor and were finalized with German Foreign Affairs Minister Julius Curtius on 5 March 1931, before being approved by Germany on 18 March.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] France opposed the customs union, stating that it was in violation of Article 88 of the Treaty of Saint-Germain-en-Laye.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] When the Nazis, led by Adolf Hitler, rose to power in the Weimar Republic, the Austrian government withdrew from economic ties.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Like Germany, Austria experienced the economic turbulence which was a result of the Great Depression, with a high unemployment rate, and unstable commerce and industry.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] During the 1920s it was a target for German investment capital.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] By 1937, rapid German rearmament increased Berlin's interest in annexing Austria, rich in raw materials and labour.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] It supplied Germany with magnesium and the products of the iron, textile and machine industries.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] It had gold and foreign currency reserves, many unemployed skilled workers, hundreds of idle factories, and large potential hydroelectric resources.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Hitler, an Austrian German by birth, picked up his German nationalist ideas at a young age.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] In vigorously and adroitly attacking the man's arguments Hitler made an impression on the other party members with his aptitude for oratory and, according to Hitler, the "professor" left the hall acknowledging unequivocal defeat.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Impressed with Hitler, Anton Drexler, then Chairman of the DAP, invited him to join the party.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Hitler accepted on 12 September 1919, becoming the party's 55th member.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] After becoming leader of the DAP, Hitler addressed a crowd on 24 February 1920, and in an effort to appeal to wider parts of the German population, the DAP was renamed the National Socialist German Workers' Party (NSDAP).
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] As its first point, the 1920 National Socialist Program stated, "We demand the unification of all Germans in the Greater Germany on the basis of the people's right to self-determination.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Hitler wrote in *Mein Kampf* (1925) that he would create a union between his birth country Austria and Germany by any means possible.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] The First Austrian Republic was dominated from the late 1920s by the Christian Social Party (CS), whose economic policies were based on the papal encyclical *Rerum novarum*.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] The First Republic gradually disintegrated in 1933, when parliament was dissolved and power was centralized in the office of the chancellor, who was empowered to rule by decree.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Rival parties, including the Austrian National Socialists, were banned, and government evolved into a corporatist, one-party government that combined the CS and the paramilitary *Heimwehr*.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] It controlled labor relations and the press.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] The new regime emphasized the Catholic elements of Austria's national identity and staunchly opposed union with Nazi Germany.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Engelbert Dollfuss and his successor, Kurt Schuschnigg, turned to Benito Mussolini's Italy for inspiration and support.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Mussolini supported the independence of Austria, largely due to his concern that Hitler would eventually press for the return of Italian territories which had once been ruled by Austria.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Afterwards Italy had formed a common front with Great Britain and France opposed to German rearmament in early 1935 in the context of German withdrawal from the International Disarmament Conference, the Stresa Front.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] However, the Stresa Front collapsed after French foreign ministry signed a pact with the USSR in early 1935, and Britain reacted by signing a naval agreement with Germany.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] After receiving Hitler's personal assurance that Germany would not seek territorial concessions from Italy, Mussolini entered into a relationship with Berlin that began with the formation of the Berlin–Rome Axis in 1936 which was formalised into a military alliance in the Pact of Steel in 1939.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] The Austrian Nazi Party failed to win any seats in the November 1930 general election, but its popularity grew in Austria after Hitler came to power in Germany.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] The idea of the country joining Germany also grew in popularity, thanks in part to a Nazi propaganda campaign which used slogans such as *Ein Volk, ein Reich, ein Führer* ("One People, One Empire, One Leader") to try to convince Austrians to advocate for an *Anschluss* to the German Reich.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] *Anschluss* might have occurred by democratic process had Austrian Nazis not begun a terrorism campaign.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] According to John Gunther in 1936, "In 1932 Austria was probably eighty percent pro-*Anschluss*".
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] When Germany permitted residents of Austria to vote on 5 March 1933, three special trains, boats and trucks brought such masses to Passau that the SS staged a ceremonial welcome.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Gunther wrote that by the end of 1933 Austrian public opinion about German annexation was at least 60% against.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] On 25 July 1934, chancellor Dollfuss was assassinated by Austrian Nazis in a failed coup.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Afterwards, leading Austrian Nazis fled to Germany but they continued to push for unification from there.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] The remaining Austrian Nazis continued terrorist attacks against Austrian governmental institutions, which caused 164 deaths and 636 injuries between 1933 and 1938.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Dollfuss's successor was Kurt Schuschnigg, who followed a political course similar to his predecessor.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] In 1935 Schuschnigg used the police to suppress Nazi supporters.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Police actions under Schuschnigg included gathering Nazis (and Social Democrats) and holding them in internment camps.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Austria between 1934 and 1938 focused on the history of Austria and opposed the absorption of Austria into Nazi Germany (according to the philosophy Austrians were "superior Germans").
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Schuschnigg called Austria the "better German state" but struggled to keep Austria independent.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] In summer 1936, Schuschnigg told Mussolini that his country had to come to an agreement with Germany.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] On 11 July 1936 he signed an agreement with German ambassador Franz von Papen, in which Schuschnigg agreed to the release of Nazis imprisoned in Austria and Germany promised to respect Austrian sovereignty.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] This did not satisfy Hitler and the pro-German Austrian Nazis grew in strength.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] In September 1936, Hitler launched the Four Year Plan that called for a dramatic increase in military spending and to make Germany as autarkic as possible with the aim of having the *Reich* ready to fight a world war by 1940.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] As the Four Year Plan fell further and further behind its targets, Hermann Göring, the chief of the Four Year Plan office, began to press for an *Anschluss* as a way of securing Austria's iron and other raw materials as a solution to the problems with the Four Year Plan.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Göring was far more interested in the return of the former German colonies in Africa than Hitler was, believing up to 1939 in the possibility of an Anglo-German alliance (an idea that Hitler had abandoned by late 1937), and wanted all Eastern Europe in the German economic sphere of influence.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Göring did not share Hitler's interest in *Lebensraum* ("living space") as for him, merely having Eastern Europe in the German economic sphere of influence was sufficient.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] In this context, having Austria annexed to Germany was the key towards bringing Eastern Europe into Göring's desired *Grossraumwirtschaft* ("greater economic space").
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Faced with problems in the Four Year Plan, Göring had become the loudest voice in Germany, calling for an *Anschluss*, even at the risk of losing an alliance with Italy.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] In April 1937, in a secret speech before a group of German industrialists, Göring stated that the only solution to the problems with meeting the steel production targets laid out by the Four Year Plan was to annex Austria, which Göring noted was rich in iron.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Göring did not give a date for the *Anschluss*, but given that Four Year Plan's targets all had to be met by September 1940, and the current problems with meeting the steel production targets, suggested that he wanted an *Anschluss* in the very near-future.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Hitler told Goebbels in the late summer of 1937 that eventually Austria would have to be taken "by force".
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] In early 1938, Hitler was seriously considering replacing Papen as ambassador to Austria with either Colonel Hermann Kriebel, the German consul in Shanghai, or Albert Forster, the *Gauleiter* of Danzig.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] On 25 January 1938, the Austrian police raided the Vienna headquarters of the Austrian Nazi Party, arresting *Gauleiter* Leopold Tavs, the deputy to Captain Josef Leopold, discovered a cache of arms and plans for a *putsch*.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Following increasing violence and demands from Hitler that Austria agree to a union, Schuschnigg met Hitler at Berchtesgaden on 12 February 1938, in an attempt to avoid the takeover of Austria.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Hitler presented Schuschnigg with a set of demands including appointing Nazi sympathizers to positions of power in the government.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] The key appointment was that of Arthur Seyss-Inquart as Minister of Public Security, with full, unlimited control of the police.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] In return Hitler would publicly reaffirm the treaty of 11 July 1936 and reaffirm his support for Austria's national sovereignty.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Browbeaten and threatened by Hitler, Schuschnigg agreed to these demands and put them into effect.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Seyss-Inquart was a long-time supporter of the Nazis who sought the union of all Germans in one state.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Leopold argues he was a moderate who favoured an evolutionary approach to union.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] He opposed the violent tactics of the Austrian Nazis, cooperated with Catholic groups, and wanted to preserve a measure of Austrian identity within Nazi Germany.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] On 20 February, Hitler made a speech before the Reichstag which was broadcast live and which for the first time was relayed also by the Austrian radio network.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] regime fought to keep Austria as an independent country.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] The Social Democrats also declared their readiness to support Schuschnigg in the event of a plebiscite under the conditions that immediately after such a plebiscite a definite negotiation be begun to include them in the Government.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] This support led Schuschnigg to announce the referendum.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Knaur, Germany believed that a defeat in a referendum was likely, and thus dispatched men to Vienna to prevent or modify the plebiscite.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] On 9 March 1938, in the face of rioting by the small, but virulent, Austrian Nazi Party and ever-expanding German demands on Austria, Chancellor Kurt Schuschnigg called a referendum (plebiscite) on the issue, to be held on 13 March.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Infuriated, on 11 March, Adolf Hitler threatened invasion of Austria, and demanded Chancellor von Schuschnigg's resignation and the appointment of the Nazi Arthur Seyss-Inquart as his replacement.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Hitler's plan was for Seyss-Inquart to call immediately for German troops to rush to Austria's aid, restoring order and giving the invasion an air of legitimacy.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] In the face of this threat, Schuschnigg informed Seyss-Inquart that the plebiscite would be cancelled.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] To secure a large majority in the referendum, Schuschnigg dismantled the one-party state.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] He agreed to legalize the Social Democrats and their trade unions in return for their support in the referendum.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] He also set the minimum voting age at 24 to exclude younger voters because the Nazi movement was most popular among the young.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] In contrast, Hitler had lowered the voting age for German elections held under Nazi rule, largely to compensate for the removal of Jews and other ethnic minorities from the German electorate following enactment of the Nuremberg Laws in 1935.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] The plan went awry when it became apparent that Hitler would not stand by while Austria declared its independence by public vote.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Hitler declared that the referendum would be subject to major fraud and that Germany would never accept it.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] In addition, the German ministry of propaganda issued press reports that riots had broken out in Austria and that large parts of the Austrian population were calling for German troops to restore order.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Schuschnigg immediately responded that reports of riots were false.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Hitler sent an ultimatum to Schuschnigg on 11 March, demanding that he hand over all power to the Austrian Nazis or face an invasion.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] The ultimatum was set to expire at noon, but was extended by two hours.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Without waiting for an answer, Hitler had already signed the order to send troops into Austria at one o'clock.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Nevertheless, the German Führer underestimated his opposition.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Schuschnigg desperately sought support for Austrian independence in the hours following the ultimatum.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Realizing that neither France nor Britain was willing to offer assistance, Schuschnigg resigned on the evening of 11 March, but President Wilhelm Miklas refused to appoint Seyss-Inquart as Chancellor.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] At 8:45 pm, Hitler, tired of waiting, ordered the invasion to commence at dawn on 12 March regardless.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Around 10 pm, a forged telegram was sent in Seyss-Inquart's name asking for German troops, since he was not yet Chancellor and was unable to do so himself.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Seyss-Inquart was not installed as Chancellor until after midnight, when Miklas resigned himself to the inevitable.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] In the radio broadcast in which Schuschnigg announced his resignation, he argued that he accepted the changes and allowed the Nazis to take over the government "to avoid the shedding of fraternal blood [*Bruderblut*]".
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Seyss-Inquart was appointed chancellor after midnight on 12 March.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] It is said that after listening to Bruckner's Seventh Symphony, Hitler cried: "How can anyone say that Austria is not German!
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] On the morning of 12 March 1938, the 8th Army of the German *Wehrmacht* crossed the border into Austria.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] The troops were greeted by cheering Austrians with Nazi salutes, Nazi flags, and flowers.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] The "invasion" without shots fired was therefore dubbed the Blumenkrieg ("Flower War").
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] For the *Wehrmacht*, the invasion was the first big test of its machinery.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Although the invading forces were badly organized and coordination among the units was poor, it mattered little because the Austrian government had ordered the Austrian Bundesheer not to resist.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] That afternoon, Hitler, riding in a car, crossed the border at his birthplace, Braunau am Inn, with a 4,000 man bodyguard.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] In the evening, he arrived at Linz and was given an enthusiastic welcome.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] 250,000 Austrians gathered in Linz to meet Adolf Hitler and support *Anschluss*.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] The enthusiasm displayed toward Hitler and the Germans surprised both Nazis and non-Nazis, as most people had believed that a majority of Austrians opposed *Anschluss*.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Many Germans from both Austria and Germany welcomed the *Anschluss* as they saw it as completing the complex and long overdue unification of all Germans into one state.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] On 13 March Seyss-Inquart announced the abrogation of Article 88 of the Treaty of Saint-Germain, which prohibited the unification of Austria and Germany, and approved the replacement of the Austrian states with *Reichsgaue*.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] The seizure of Austria demonstrated once again Hitler's aggressive territorial ambitions, and, once again, the failure of the British and the French to take action against him for violating the Versailles Treaty.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Their lack of will emboldened him toward further aggression.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] I can only say: even in death they cannot stop lying.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] I have in the course of my political struggle won much love from my people, but when I crossed the former frontier (into Austria) there met me such a stream of love as I have never experienced.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Hitler's popularity reached an unprecedented peak after he fulfilled the *Anschluss* because he had completed the long-awaited idea of a Greater Germany.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Bismarck had not chosen to include Austria in his 1871 unification of Germany, and there was genuine support from Germans in both Austria and Germany for an *Anschluss*.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Hitler's forces suppressed all opposition.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Before the first German soldier crossed the border, Heinrich Himmler and a few Schutzstaffel (SS) officers landed in Vienna to arrest prominent representatives of the First Republic, such as Richard Schmitz, Leopold Figl, Friedrich Hillegeist, and Franz Olah.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] During the few weeks between the *Anschluss* and the plebiscite, authorities rounded up Social Democrats, Communists, other potential political dissenters, and Austrian Jews, and imprisoned them or sent them to concentration camps.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Within a few days of 12 March, 70,000 people had been arrested.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] The disused northwest railway station in Vienna was converted into a makeshift concentration camp.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] American historian Evan Burr Bukey warned that the plebiscite result needs to be taken with "great caution".
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] The plebiscite was subject to large-scale Nazi propaganda and to the abrogation of the voting rights of around 360,000 people (8% of the eligible voting population), mainly political enemies such as former members of left-wing parties and Austrian citizens of Jewish or Romani origin.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] American historian Evan Bukey argues that there was a genuine German nationalist feeling in Austria amongst at least a part of the population, and those holding antisemitic sentiments were more than ready to "fulfill their duty" in the "Greater German Reich".
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Bukey also states that since the Social Democratic Party of Austria leader Karl Renner and the highest representative of the Roman Catholic church in Austria Cardinal Theodor Innitzer both endorsed the *Anschluss*, approximately two-thirds of Austrians might have voted for it.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Similary, Austrian historian Gerhard Botz claimed that the Nazis did not falsify the results of the referendum and assumed that the "yes"-votes were in the range of 90 to 99 percent.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] On the contrary, Julie Thorpe notes that endorsements of people such as Renner "do not stand on their own as evidence for broad pan-German sympathies amongst Austria’s working population".
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] British historian Donny Gluckstein notes that Austrian socialists reacted with "disgust" to Renner's endorsement of Anschluss, provoking a split in the SPÖ.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Austrian left circles vehemently opposed Anschluss, and Renner's declaration prompted many to defect to Revolutionary Socialists under Otto Bauer or the KPÖ.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] The relevance of Innitzer's endorsement is also disputed – he was reportedly "despised" by Austrian workers, and the Anschluss sparked Catholic protests in Austria under the slogan "Our Führer is Christ" (rather than Hitler).
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] According to the Austrian historian Alfred D.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Low, one of the reasons why Germany did not allow the plebiscite to be held by the Austrian government was that the Nazi regime feared to be defeated at the polls; Low states that in 1938, there was "majority support to Austria's independence".
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] According to Hungarian historian Oszkár Jászi, writing in 1938, the idea of *Anschluss* was opposed amongst most political circles in Austria.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Jászi noted that "the annihilation of the German labor movement showed to Austrian socialism what it could expect from an Anschluss under Nazi rule", while "Austrian Catholicism realized what its fate would be under a system which crushed the great Catholic Party of Germany, the Centrum".
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] It was also opposed by other groups, such as the Austrian Jews as well as "old Hapsburgist officers and officials and by a considerable part of Austrian capitalism".
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Most contemporary writers estimated that about two-thirds of Austrians wanted Austria to remain independent.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] How many Austrians behind closed doors were against the *Anschluss* remains unknown, but only one "unhappy face" of an Austrian in public when the Germans marched into Austria has ever been produced.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] According to some Gestapo reports, only a quarter to a third of Austrian voters in Vienna were in favour of the *Anschluss*.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] In most rural areas, especially in Tyrol, the support for the Anschluss was even lower.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] According to Evan Burr Bukey, no more than one-third of Austrians ever fully supported Nazism during the existence of Nazi Germany.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] According to the estimates of the Austrian government, with the voting age of 24, about 70% of Austrians would have voted to preserve the Austrian independence.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Czech-American historian Radomír Luža estimated that between 65% and 75% of Austrians supported the continuation of Austrian independence.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] About a quarter of the Austrian population was estimated to be supportive of the NSDAP.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] The newly installed Nazis, within two days, transferred power to Germany, and *Wehrmacht* troops entered Austria to enforce the *Anschluss*.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] The Nazis held a controlled plebiscite (*Volksabstimmung*) in the whole Reich within the following month, asking the people to ratify the *fait accompli*, and claimed that 99.7561% of the votes cast in Austria were in favor.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Although the Allies were committed to upholding the terms of the Treaty of Versailles and those of St.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Germain, which specifically prohibited the union of Austria and Germany, their reaction was only verbal and moderate.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] No military confrontation took place, and even the strongest voices against the annexation, particularly, France, and Great Britain remained at peace.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] The loudest verbal protest was voiced by the government of Mexico.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Germany, which had a shortage of steel and a weak balance of payments, gained iron ore mines in the Erzberg and 748 million RM in the reserves of Austria's central bank Oesterreichische Nationalbank, more than twice its own cash.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] In the years that followed, some bank accounts were transferred from Austria to Germany as "enemy property accounts".
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] The campaign against the Jews began immediately after the *Anschluss*.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] They were driven through the streets of Vienna, their homes and shops were plundered.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Jewish men and women were forced to wash away pro-independence slogans painted on the streets of Vienna ahead of the failed 13 March plebiscite.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Jewish actresses from the Theater in der Josefstadt were forced to clean toilets by the SA.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] The process of Aryanisation began, and Jews were driven out of public life within months.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] These events reached a climax in the Kristallnacht pogrom of 9–10 November 1938.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] All synagogues and prayer houses in Vienna were destroyed, as well as in other Austrian cities such as Salzburg.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] The Stadttempel was the sole survivor due to its location in a residential district which prevented it from being burned down.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Most Jewish shops were plundered and closed.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Over 6,000 Jews were arrested overnight, the majority deported to Dachau concentration camp in the following days.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] The Nuremberg Laws applied in Austria from May 1938, later reinforced with innumerable antisemitic decrees.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Jews were gradually robbed of their freedoms, blocked from almost all professions, shut out of schools and universities, and forced to wear the yellow badge from September 1941.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] The Nazis dissolved Jewish organisations and institutions, hoping to force Jews to emigrate.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Their plans succeeded—by the end of 1941, 130,000 Jews had left Vienna, 30,000 of whom went to the United States.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] They left behind all of their property, but were forced to pay the Reich Flight Tax, a tax on all émigrés from Nazi Germany; some received financial support from international aid organisations so that they could pay this tax.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] The majority of the Jews who had stayed in Vienna eventually became victims of the Holocaust.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Of the more than 65,000 Viennese Jews who were deported to concentration camps, fewer than 2,000 survived.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] The *Anschluss* was given immediate effect by legislative act on 13 March, subject to ratification by a referendum.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Austria became the province of Ostmark, and Seyss-Inquart was appointed governor.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] The referendum was held on 10 April and officially recorded a support of 99.7% of the voters.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] While historians concur that the votes were accurately counted, the process was neither free nor secret.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Officials were present directly beside the voting booths and received the voting ballot by hand (in contrast to a secret vote where the voting ballot is inserted into a closed box).
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] In the referendum on 10 April, 73.3% of votes in Innervillgraten were in favor of the *Anschluss*, which was the lowest number of all Austrian municipalities.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Austria remained part of Germany until the end of World War II.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] A provisional government in Allied-occupied Austria declared the *Anschluss* "null und nichtig" (null and void) on 27 April 1945.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p01] Henceforth, Austria was recognized as a separate country, although it remained divided into occupation zones and controlled by the Allied Commission until 1955, when the Austrian State Treaty restored its sovereignty.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] In March 1938 the local Gauleiter of Gmunden, Upper Austria, gave a speech to the local Austrians and told them in plain terms that all "traitors" of Austria were to be thrown into the newly opened concentration camp at Mauthausen-Gusen.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] The camp became notorious for its cruelty and barbarism.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] During its existence an estimated 200,000 people died, half of whom were directly killed.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] The antigypsy sentiment was implemented initially most harshly in Austria when between 1938 and 1939 the Nazis arrested around 2,000 Romani men who were sent to Dachau and 1,000 Romani women who were sent to Ravensbrück.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] Starting in 1939, Austrian Romani had to register themselves to local authorities.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] The Nazis began to publish articles linking the Romani with criminality.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] Until 1942, the Nazis had made a distinction between "pure Gypsies" and "Gypsy *Mischlinges*" ("mixlings" or "half-breeds").
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] However, Nazi racial research claimed that 90% of Romani were of mixed ancestry.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] Subsequently, the Nazis ordered that the Romani were to be treated on the same level as the Jews.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] After breaking off the negotiations regarding the position of the Catholic Church in Austria, Cardinal Theodor Innitzer (a political figure of the CS) was intimidated into supporting the Anschluss after being assaulted.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] Vatican Radio, however, broadcast a strong denunciation of the German action, and Cardinal Eugenio Pacelli, the Vatican Secretary of State, ordered Innitzer to report to Rome.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] Before meeting the Pope, Innitzer met Pacelli, who had been outraged by Innitzer's statement.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] He told Innitzer to retract his statement; he was made to sign a new statement, issued on behalf of all the Austrian bishops, that stated: "The solemn declaration of the Austrian bishops... was clearly not intended to be an approval of something that was not and is not compatible with God's law".
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] Describing the Church's reaction to Anschluss, historian Ronald J.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] The Vatican newspaper reported that the German bishops' earlier statement had been issued without approval from Rome.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] The Vatican condemned Nazism in its newspaper *L'Osservatore Romano*, and forbade Catholics from following their ideas or supporting Anschluss.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] On 11 March 1938, one day before the occupation of Austria by the Wehrmacht, the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Vienna issued an appeal to Austrians: "As Austrian citizens, we stand and we fight for a free and independent Austria".
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] Robert Kauer, president of the minority Lutheran Church in Austria, greeted Hitler on 13 March as "saviour of the 350,000 German Protestants in Austria and liberator from a five-year hardship".
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] Karl Renner, the most famous Social Democrat of the First Republic, announced his support for the *Anschluss* and appealed to all Austrians to vote in favour of it on 10 April.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] The international response to the *Anschluss* was publicly moderate.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] *The Times* commented that 300 years before, Scotland had joined England as well and that this event would not really differ much.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] On 14 March, the British Prime Minister, Neville Chamberlain spoke about the "Austrian situation" in the House of Commons.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] He noted that the British ambassador in Berlin objected to the use of "coercion, backed by force" that would undermine Austria's independence.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] On 18 March 1938, the German government communicated to the Secretary General of the League of Nations about the inclusion of Austria.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] And the next day in Geneva, the Mexican Delegate to the International Office of Labor, Isidro Fabela, voiced an energetic protest, stronger than that expressed by European countries, denouncing the annexation of Austria by Nazi Germany.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] The word *Anschluss* is properly translated as "joinder", "connection", "unification", or "political union".
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] In contrast, the German word *Annektierung* (military annexation) was not used, and is not commonly used now, to describe the union of Austria and Germany in 1938.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] The word *Anschluss* had been widespread before 1938 describing an incorporation of Austria into Germany.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] Calling the incorporation of Austria into Germany an "Anschluss," that is a "unification" or "joinder", was also part of the propaganda used in 1938 by Nazi Germany to create the impression that the union was not coerced.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] Hitler described the incorporation of Austria as a *Heimkehr*, a return to its original home.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] The word *Anschluss* has endured since 1938.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] Some sources, like the *Encyclopædia Britannica*, describe the *Anschluss* as an "annexation" rather than a union.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] The *Anschluss* was among the first major steps in Austrian-born Hitler's desire to create a Greater German Reich that was to include all ethnic Germans and all the lands and territories that the German Empire had lost after the First World War.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] Although Austria was predominantly ethnically German and had been part of the Holy Roman Empire until it dissolved in 1806 and the German Confederation until 1866 after the defeat in the Austro-Prussian War, it had never been a part of the German Empire.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] The unification of Germany brought about by Otto von Bismarck created that Prussian-dominated entity in 1871, with Austria, Prussia's rival for dominance of the German states, explicitly excluded.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] Prior to annexing Austria in 1938, Nazi Germany had remilitarized the Rhineland, and the Saar region was returned to Germany after 15 years of occupation through a plebiscite.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] After the *Anschluss*, Hitler targeted Czechoslovakia, provoking an international crisis which led to the Munich Agreement in September 1938, giving Nazi Germany control of the industrial Sudetenland, which had a predominantly ethnic German population.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] In March 1939, Hitler then dismantled Czechoslovakia by recognising the independence of Slovakia and making the rest of the nation a protectorate.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] That same year, Memelland was returned from Lithuania.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] With the *Anschluss*, the Republic of Austria ceased to exist as an independent state.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] At the end of World War II, a Provisional Austrian Government under Karl Renner was set up by conservatives, Social Democrats and Communists on 27 April 1945 (when Vienna had already been occupied by the Red Army).
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] It cancelled the *Anschluss* the same day and was legally recognized by the Allies in the following months.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] In 1955 the Austrian State Treaty re-established Austria as a sovereign state.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] The Moscow Declaration is said to have a somewhat complex drafting history.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] The declaration was mostly intended to serve as propaganda aimed at stirring Austrian resistance.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] Although some Austrians aided Jews and are counted as Righteous Among the Nations, there never was an effective Austrian armed resistance of the sort found in other countries under German occupation.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] Arthur Seyss-Inquart and Franz von Papen, in particular, were both indicted under count one (conspiracy to commit crimes against peace) specifically for their activities in support of the Austrian Nazi Party and the *Anschluss*, but neither was convicted of this count.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] In acquitting von Papen, the court noted that his actions were in its view political immoralities but not crimes under its charter.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] Seyss-Inquart was convicted of other serious war crimes, most of which took place in Poland and the Netherlands, was sentenced to death and executed.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] From 1949 to 1988, many Austrians sought comfort in the idea of Austria as being the first victim of the Nazis (*Opferthese*).
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] Although the Nazi party was promptly banned, Austria did not have the same thorough process of denazification that was imposed on Germany.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] Lacking outside pressure for political reform, factions of Austrian society tried for a long time to advance the view that the *Anschluss* was "only an annexation at the point of a bayonet".
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] The state treaty, alongside the subsequent Austrian declaration of permanent neutrality, marked important milestones for the solidification of Austria's independent national identity during the course of the following decades.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] As Austrian politicians of the left and right attempted to reconcile their differences to avoid the violent conflict that had dominated the First Republic, discussions of both Austrian Nazism and Austria's role during the Nazi-era were largely avoided.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] Still, the Austrian People's Party (ÖVP) had advanced, and still advances, the argument that the establishment of the Dollfuss dictatorship was necessary to maintain Austrian independence.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] On the other hand, the Austrian Social Democratic Party (SPÖ) argues that the Dollfuss dictatorship stripped the country of the democratic resources necessary to repel Hitler; yet it ignores the fact that Hitler himself was a native of Austria.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] It has also helped the Austrians develop their own national identity as before.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] After World War II and the fall of Nazi Germany the political ideology of Pan-Germanism fell into disfavor and is now seen by the majority of German-speaking people as taboo.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] Unlike earlier in the 20th century when there was no Austrian identity separate from a German one, in 1987 only 6% of the Austrians identified themselves as "Germans." A survey carried out in 2008 found that 82% of Austrians considered themselves to be their own nation.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] For decades, the victim theory remained largely undisputed in Austria.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] The public was rarely forced to confront the legacy of Nazi Germany.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] One of those occasions arose in 1965, when Taras Borodajkewycz, a professor of economic history, made antisemitic remarks following the death of Ernst Kirchweger, a concentration camp survivor killed by a right-wing protester during riots.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] It was not until the 1980s that Austrians confronted their mixed past on a large scale.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] The catalyst for the *Vergangenheitsbewältigung* (struggle to come to terms with the past) was the Waldheim affair.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] Kurt Waldheim, a successful candidate in the 1986 Austrian presidential election and former UN Secretary-General, was accused of having been a member of the Nazi party and of the Sturmabteilung (SA).
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] He was later absolved of direct involvement in war crimes.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] The Waldheim affair started the first serious discussions about Austria's past and the *Anschluss*.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] Another factor was the rise of Jörg Haider and the Freedom Party of Austria (FPÖ) in the 1980s.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] The party had combined elements of the pan-German right with free-market liberalism since its foundation in 1955, but after Haider ascended to the party chairmanship in 1986, the liberal elements became increasingly marginalized.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] Haider began to openly use nationalist and anti-immigrant rhetoric.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] He was criticised for using the *völkisch* (ethnic) definition of national interest ("Austria for Austrians") and his apologetics for Austria's past, notably calling members of the Waffen-SS "men of honour".
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] Following a dramatic rise in electoral support in the 1990s that peaked in the 1999 elections, the FPÖ entered a coalition with the Austrian People's Party (ÖVP), led by Wolfgang Schüssel.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] The coalition prompted the regular *Donnerstagsdemonstrationen* (Thursday demonstrations) in protest against the government, which took place on the Heldenplatz where Hitler had greeted the masses during the *Anschluss*.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] Haider's tactics and rhetoric, often criticised as sympathetic to Nazism, forced Austrians to reconsider their relationship to the past.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] Haider's coalition partner, former Chancellor Wolfgang Schüssel, in a 2000 interview with *The Jerusalem Post*, reiterated the "first victim" theory.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] The political discussions and soul-searching were reflected in other aspects of culture.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] Thomas Bernhard's last play, *Heldenplatz* (1988), generated controversy even before it was produced, fifty years after Hitler's entrance to the city.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] Bernhard made the historic elimination of references to Hitler's reception in Vienna emblematic of Austrian attempts to claim its history and culture under questionable criteria.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] Many politicians called Bernhard a *Nestbeschmutzer* (damaging the reputation of his country) and openly demanded that the play should not be staged in Vienna's Burgtheater.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] Waldheim, still president, called the play "a crude insult to the Austrian people".
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] In the Federal Republic of Germany the *Vergangenheitsbewältigung* ("struggle to come to terms with the past") has been partially institutionalised in literary, cultural, political, and educational contexts.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] Its membership was based on recommendations from various quarters, including Simon Wiesenthal and Yad Vashem.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] The Commission delivered its report in 2003.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] The Simon Wiesenthal Center continues to criticise Austria (as recently as June 2005) for its alleged historical and ongoing unwillingness to aggressively pursue investigations and trials against Nazis for war crimes and crimes against humanity from the 1970s onwards.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] In 2003, the Center launched a worldwide effort named "Operation: Last Chance" in order to collect further information about those Nazis still alive that are potentially subject to prosecution.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] Although reports issued shortly thereafter credited Austria for initiating large-scale investigations, there has been one case where criticism of Austrian authorities arose recently: The Center put 92-year-old Croatian Milivoj Asner on its 2005 top ten list.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] Asner fled to Austria in 2004 after Croatia announced it would start investigations in the case of war crimes he may have been involved in.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] In response to objections about Asner's continued freedom, Austria's federal government deferred to either extradition requests from Croatia or prosecutorial actions from Klagenfurt, claiming reason of dementia in 2008.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] Milivoj Ašner died on 14 June 2011 at the age of 98 in his room in a Caritas nursing home still in Klagenfurt.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] The occurrence of the Sudeten crisis in early 1938 led to the autumn Munich Agreement after which Nazi Germany occupied the Sudetenland.
[src:austrian-standards-international/anschluss-p02] These events taken as a whole can be seen as a mimeograph of the Anschluss page in Hitler's playbook.
[src:austrian-standards-international/asc-x9] The **Accredited Standards Committee X9** (ASC X9, Inc.) is an ANSI (American National Standards Institute) accredited standards developing organization, responsible for developing voluntary open consensus standards for the financial services industry in the U.S.
[src:austrian-standards-international/asc-x9] Membership in ASC X9 is open to all U.S. domiciled companies and organizations in the financial services industry.
[src:austrian-standards-international/asc-x9] The committee was founded in 1974 under the American National Standards Institute, to develop financial industry standards following a surge in electronic banking, automated clearing, and data security needs.
[src:austrian-standards-international/asc-x9] In 1984 it played a major role role in supporting the Check Clearing for the 21st Century Act (Check 21) through development of check image exchange and related standards.
[src:austrian-standards-international/asc-x9] In the 1990s it expanded its cryptography standards, developing foundational specifications for secure data exchange and public key infrastructures (e.g., X9.42, X9.73, X9.24).
[src:austrian-standards-international/asc-x9] In 2001, the organization was incorporated as ASC X9, Inc., transitioning from a pure ANSI committee to a non-profit industry consortium still accredited by ANSI.
[src:austrian-standards-international/asc-x9] During the 2000s and 2010s it joined with international bodies like ISO/TC 68, helping shape ISO 20022 and other global standards for payments and securities messaging.
[src:austrian-standards-international/asc-x9] The Accredited Standards Committee X9 develops, establishes, maintains, and promotes standards for the Financial Services Industry in the United States in order to facilitate delivery of financial services and products.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The area of today's Austria has been inhabited since at least the Paleolithic period.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Around 400 BC, it was inhabited by the Celts and then annexed by the Romans in the late 1st century BC.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Christianization in the region began in the 4th and 5th centuries, during the late Roman period, followed by the arrival of numerous Germanic tribes during the Migration Period.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Austria, as an unified state, emerged from the remnants of the Eastern and Hungarian March at the end of the first millennium, first as a frontier march of the Holy Roman Empire, it then developed into a Duchy in 1156, and was made an Archduchy in 1453.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Being the heartland of the Habsburg monarchy since the late 13th century, Austria was a major imperial power in Central Europe for centuries and from the 16th century, Vienna also served as the Holy Roman Empire's administrative capital.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The Holy Roman Empire was dissolved in 1806, two years after Austria had established its own empire, which became a great power and one of the largest states in Europe.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The empire's defeat in wars and the loss of territories in the 1860s paved the way for the establishment of Austria-Hungary in 1867.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] After the assassination of Archduke Franz Ferdinand in 1914, Emperor Franz Joseph declared war on Serbia, which rapidly escalated into World War I.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The empire's defeat and subsequent collapse led to the proclamation of the Republic of German-Austria in 1918 and the First Austrian Republic in 1919.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] During the interwar period, anti-parliamentarian sentiments culminated in the formation of an Austrofascist dictatorship under Engelbert Dollfuss in 1934.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] A year before the outbreak of World War II, Austria was annexed into Nazi Germany by Adolf Hitler, and it became a sub-national division.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] After its liberation in 1945 and a decade of Allied occupation, the country regained its sovereignty and declared its perpetual neutrality in 1955.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Austria is a semi-presidential representative democracy with a popularly elected president as head of state and a chancellor as head of government and chief executive.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Austria has the 13th highest nominal GDP per capita with high standards of living.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The country has been a member of the United Nations since 1955 and of the European Union since 1995.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] It hosts the Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe (OSCE) and the Organization of the Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) and is a founding member of the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) and Interpol.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] It also signed the Schengen Agreement in 1995, and adopted the euro currency in 1999.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The native name for Austria, *Österreich*, derives from the Old High German *Ostarrîchi*, which meant "eastern realm", can be also translated as "eastern empire" or "eastern kingdom", and which first appeared in the "Ostarrîchi document" of 996.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] This word is probably a translation of Medieval Latin *Marchia orientalis* into a local (Bavarian) dialect.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Austria was a prefecture of Bavaria created in 976.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The word "Austria" is a Latinisation of the German name and was first recorded in the 12th century.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] At the time, the Danube basin of Austria (Upper and Lower Austria) was the easternmost extent of Bavaria.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The area that is now Austria was settled in pre-Roman times by various Celtic tribes, having been the core of the Hallstatt culture by the 6th century BC.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The city of Hallstatt, in fact, has the oldest archaeological evidence of the Celts in Europe.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The Celtic Kingdom of Noricum that included most of modern Austria and parts of modern Slovenia was conquered by the Roman Empire in 16 BC and made a province called Noricum which lasted until 476.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The regions of today's Austria which were not located within the province of Noricum were divided between the Roman provinces of Pannonia, which encompassed parts of eastern Austria, and Raetia, which encompassed the areas of present-day Vorarlberg and Tyrol.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Present-day Petronell-Carnuntum in eastern Austria was an important army camp turned capital city in what became known as the Pannonia Superior.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Carnuntum was home to 50,000 people for nearly 400 years.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] After the fall of the Roman Empire, the area was first invaded by the Germanic Rugii which made this region part of their "Rugiland".
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] In 487, most of modern Austria was conquered by Odoacer, a barbarian soldier and statesman from the Middle Danube, which incorporated most of today's Austria in his Kingdom of Italy.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] By 493, it was conquered by the Germanic Ostrogoths which created their own kingdom, the Ostrogothic Kingdom.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Following the Kingdom's fall the area was invaded by the Alemanni, Baiuvarii, Slavs, and Avars.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Charlemagne, King of the Franks, conquered the area in 788, encouraged colonisation, and introduced Christianity.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] As part of Eastern Francia, the core areas that now encompass Austria were bequeathed to the house of Babenberg.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The area was known as the *marchia Orientalis* and was given to Leopold I in 976.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The first record showing the name Austria is from 996, where it is written as *Ostarrîchi*, referring to the territory of the Babenberg March.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] In 1156, the Privilegium Minus elevated Austria to the status of a duchy.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] In 1192, the Babenbergs also acquired the Duchy of Styria.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] With the death of Frederick II in 1246, the line of the Babenbergs was extinguished.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] As a result, Ottokar II of Bohemia effectively assumed control of the duchies of Austria, Styria, and Carinthia.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] His reign came to an end with his defeat at Dürnkrut at the hands of Rudolph I of Germany in 1278.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Thereafter, until World War I, Austria's history was largely that of its ruling dynasty, the Habsburgs.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] In the 14th and 15th centuries, the Habsburgs began to accumulate other provinces in the vicinity of the Duchy of Austria.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] In 1438, Duke Albert V of Austria was chosen as the successor to his father-in-law, Emperor Sigismund.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Although Albert himself only reigned for a year, henceforth every emperor of the Holy Roman Empire was a Habsburg, with only one exception.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The Habsburgs also began to accumulate territory far from the hereditary lands.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] In 1477, Archduke Maximilian, only son of Emperor Frederick III, married the heiress Maria of Burgundy, thus acquiring most of the Netherlands for the family.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] In 1496, his son Philip the Fair married Joanna the Mad, the heiress of Castile and Aragon, thus acquiring Spain and its Italian, African, Asian, and New World appendages for the Habsburgs.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] In 1526, following the Battle of Mohács, Bohemia and the part of Hungary not occupied by the Ottomans came under Austrian rule.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Ottoman expansion into Hungary led to frequent conflicts between the two empires, particularly evident in the Long War of 1593 to 1606.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The Turks made incursions into Styria nearly 20 times, of which some are cited as "burning, pillaging, and taking thousands of slaves".
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] In late September 1529, Suleiman the Magnificent launched the first siege of Vienna, which unsuccessfully ended, according to Ottoman historians, with the snowfalls of an early beginning winter.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] During the long reign of Leopold I, Holy Roman Emperor following the successful defence of Vienna against the Turks in 1683, under the command of the King of Poland John III Sobieski, the Great Turkish War resulted in most of Hungary being controlled by Austria.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] This arrangement was formalized in the Treaty of Karlowitz in 1699.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Charles VI, Holy Roman Emperor relinquished many of the gains the empire made in the previous years.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] He enjoyed the imminent extinction of the House of Habsburg.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Charles VI was willing to offer concrete advantages in territory and authority in exchange for recognition of the Pragmatic Sanction of 1713.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Therefore, his daughter Maria Theresa was recognized as his heir.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] With the rise of Prussia, the Austria–Prussia rivalry began in Germany.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Austria participated, together with Prussia and Russia, in the first and the third of the three Partitions of Poland in 1772 and 1795 respectively.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Austria engaged in war with Revolutionary France, as part of the First and Second Coalitions, and subsequently in the Napoleonic Wars.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] From 1792 to 1801, the Austrians had suffered 754,700 casualties.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The Hapsburg rulers of Austria and the Holy Roman Empire suffered successive defeats at the hands of Napoleon Bonaparte.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] To protect their status as an imperial dynasty after Napoleon proclaimed the French Empire, the Empire of Austria was founded in 1804, and to prevent Napoleon from claiming their previous Imperial throne, the Holy Roman Empire was abolished 1806.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] In 1814, Austria was part of the coalition of Allied forces that invaded France and brought to an end the Napoleonic Wars.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The Austrian Empire emerged from the Congress of Vienna in 1815 as one of the continent's four dominant powers and a recognized great power.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The same year, the German Confederation (*Deutscher Bund*) was founded under the presidency of Austria.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Because of unsolved social, political, and national conflicts, the German lands were shaken by the 1848 revolutions aiming to create a unified Germany.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The possibilities for a unified Germany were: a Greater Germany or a Greater Austria or a German Confederation without Austria at all.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] In 1864, Austria and Prussia fought together against Denmark and secured the independence from Denmark of the duchies of Schleswig and Holstein.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] As they could not agree on how the two duchies should be administered, though they fought the Austro-Prussian War in 1866.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Defeated by Prussia in the Battle of Königgrätz, Austria had to leave the German Confederation and no longer took part in German politics.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] As Austria's Habsburg monarchy was not willing to join its German-speaking territory to the German Empire of 1871, and relinquish its non-German-speaking territories, the crown of the newly formed empire was offered to the Prussian King Friedrich Wilhelm IV.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] To settle issues lingering from the suppressed Hungarian Revolution of 1848, the Austro-Hungarian Compromise of 1867, the *Ausgleich*, provided for a dual sovereignty, the Austrian Empire and the Kingdom of Hungary, under Franz Joseph I.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The Austrian-Hungarian rule of this diverse empire included various groups, including Germans, Hungarians, Croats, Czechs, Poles, Rusyns, Serbs, Slovaks, Slovenes, and Ukrainians, as well as large Italian and Romanian communities.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] As a result, ruling Austria-Hungary became increasingly difficult in an age of emerging nationalist movements, requiring considerable reliance on an expanded secret police.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Many Austrian Germans of all different social circles such as Georg Ritter von Schönerer promoted strong pan-Germanism in the hope of reinforcing an ethnic German identity amongst Austrian Germans and the annexation of Austria to Germany (*Anschluss*).
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Some Austrians such as Karl Lueger also used pan-Germanism as a form of populism to further their own political goals.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Austria's exclusion from Germany caused many Austrians a problem with their national identity and prompted the Social Democratic Leader Otto Bauer to state that it was "the conflict between our Austrian and German character".
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The Austro-Hungarian Empire caused ethnic tension between the German Austrians and the other ethnic groups.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Many Austrians, especially those involved with the pan-German movements, desired a reinforcement of an ethnic German identity and hoped that the empire would collapse, which would allow an annexation of Austria by Germany.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Many Austrian pan-German nationalists protested passionately against minister-president Kasimir Count Badeni's language decree of 1897, which made German and Czech co-official languages in Bohemia and required new government officials to be fluent in both languages.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] This meant in practice that the civil service would almost exclusively hire Czechs because most middle-class Czechs spoke German but not the other way around.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The support of ultramontane Catholic politicians and clergy for this reform triggered the launch of the *Away from Rome* movement, which was initiated by supporters of Schönerer and called on "German" Christians to leave the Roman Catholic Church.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] As the Second Constitutional Era began in the Ottoman Empire, Austria-Hungary took the opportunity to annex Bosnia and Herzegovina in 1908.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Over one million Austro-Hungarian soldiers died in World War I.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] On 21 October 1918, the elected German members of the *Reichsrat* (parliament of Imperial Austria) met in Vienna as the Provisional National Assembly for German Austria (*Provisorische Nationalversammlung für Deutschösterreich*).
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] On 30 October the assembly founded the Republic of German-Austria by appointing a government, called *Staatsrat*.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] This new government was invited by the Emperor to take part in the decision on the planned armistice with Italy but refrained from this business.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] This left the responsibility for the end of the war, on 3 November 1918, solely to the emperor and his government.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] On 11 November, the emperor, advised by ministers of the old and the new governments, declared he would not take part in state business any more; on 12 November, German-Austria, by law, declared itself to be a democratic republic and part of the new German republic.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The constitution, renaming the *Staatsrat* as *Bundesregierung* (federal government) and *Nationalversammlung* as *Nationalrat* (national council) was passed on 10 November 1920.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The Treaty of Saint-Germain of 1919 (for Hungary the Treaty of Trianon of 1920) confirmed and consolidated the new order of Central Europe which to a great extent had been established in November 1918, creating new states and altering others.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The German-speaking parts of Austria which had been part of Austria-Hungary were reduced to a rump state named the Republic of German-Austria (German: *Republik Deutschösterreich*), though excluding the predominantly German-speaking South Tyrol.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The desire for the annexation of Austria to Germany was a popular opinion shared by all social circles in both Austria and Germany.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] On 12 November, German-Austria was declared a republic, and named Social Democrat Karl Renner as provisional chancellor.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] On the same day it drafted a provisional constitution that stated that "German-Austria is a democratic republic" (Article 1) and "German-Austria is an integral part of the German Reich" (Article 2).
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The Treaty of Saint Germain and the Treaty of Versailles explicitly forbade union between Austria and Germany.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The treaties also forced German-Austria to rename itself as "Republic of Austria" which consequently led to the first Austrian Republic.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Over three million German-speaking Austrians found themselves living outside the new Austrian Republic as minorities in the newly formed or enlarged states of Czechoslovakia, Yugoslavia, Hungary, and Italy.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] These included the provinces of South Tyrol, and German Bohemia.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The status of German Bohemia and Sudetenland later played a role in World War II.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The border between Austria and the Kingdom of Yugoslavia was settled with the Carinthian Plebiscite in October 1920 and allocated the major part of the territory of the former Austro-Hungarian Crownland of Carinthia to Austria.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] This set the border on the Karawanks mountain range, with many Slovenes remaining in Austria.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] After the war, inflation began to devalue the Krone, which was still Austria's currency.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] In the autumn of 1922, Austria was granted an international loan supervised by the League of Nations.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The purpose of the loan was to avert bankruptcy, stabilise the currency, and improve Austria's general economic condition.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The loan meant that Austria passed from an independent state to the control exercised by the League of Nations.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] In 1925, the *Austrian schilling* was introduced, replacing the Krone at a rate of 10,000:1.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Later, it was nicknamed the "Alpine dollar" due to its stability.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] From 1925 to 1929 the economy enjoyed a short high before nearly crashing after Black Tuesday.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The First Austrian Republic lasted until 1933, when Chancellor Engelbert Dollfuss, using what he called "self-switch-off of Parliament", established an autocratic regime tending towards Italian fascism.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The two big parties at this time, the Social Democrats and the Conservatives, had paramilitary armies; the Social Democrats' *Republikanischer Schutzbund* was now declared illegal, but was still operative as the 12–15 February 1934 Austrian Civil War broke out.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] In February 1934, several members of the *Schutzbund* were executed, the Social Democratic party was outlawed, and many of its members were imprisoned or emigrated.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] On 1 May 1934, the Austrofascists imposed a new constitution ("Maiverfassung") which cemented Dollfuss's power, but on 25 July he was assassinated in an Austrian Nazi coup attempt.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] His successor Kurt Schuschnigg acknowledged the fact that Austria was a "German state" and he also believed that Austrians were "better Germans" but he wished that Austria would remain independent.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] He announced a referendum on 9 March 1938, to be held on 13 March, concerning Austria's independence from Germany.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] On 12 March 1938, Austrian Nazis took over the government, while German troops occupied the country, which prevented Schuschnigg's referendum from taking place.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] 'joining' or 'connection') of Austria was officially declared.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Two days later, Austrian-born Adolf Hitler announced what he called the "reunification" of his home country with the "rest of the German Reich" on Vienna's Heldenplatz.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] He established a referendum which confirmed the union with Germany in April 1938.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Parliamentary elections were held in Germany (including recently annexed Austria) on 10 April 1938.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] They were the final elections to the Reichstag during Nazi rule, and they took the form of a single-question referendum asking whether voters approved of a single Nazi-party list for the 813-member Reichstag, as well as the recent annexation of Austria (the *Anschluss*).
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Jews, Roma and Sinti were not allowed to vote.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Turnout in the election was officially 99.5%, with 98.9% voting "yes".
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] In the case of Austria, Adolf Hitler's native soil, 99.71% of an electorate of 4,484,475 officially went to the ballots, with a positive tally of 99.73 percent.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Although most Austrians favoured the *Anschluss*, in certain parts of Austria, the German soldiers were not always welcomed with flowers and joy, especially in Vienna, which had Austria's largest Jewish population.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] On 13 March 1938, Austria was annexed by the Third Reich and ceased to exist as an independent country (the *Anschluss*).
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The Aryanisation of the wealth of Jewish Austrians started immediately in mid-March, with a so-called "wild" (i.e. extra-legal) phase, but it was soon structured legally and bureaucratically so the assets which Jewish citizens possessed could be stripped from them.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] At that time, Adolf Eichmann, who grew up in Austria, was transferred to Vienna and ordered to persecute the Jews.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] During the November pogrom in 1938 ("Reichskristallnacht"), Jews and Jewish institutions such as synagogues were subjected to violent attacks in Vienna, Klagenfurt, Linz, Graz, Salzburg, Innsbruck and several cities in Lower Austria.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Otto von Habsburg, a vehement opponent of the Nazis, the last Crown Prince of Austria-Hungary, an honorary citizen of hundreds of places in Austria and partly envisaged by Schuschnigg as a monarchical option, was in Belgium at the time.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] He spoke out against the Anschluss and was then wanted by the Nazi regime and his property would have been expropriated and he would have been shot immediately if he were caught.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] In 1938, the Nazis renamed Austria the "Ostmark", a name which it had until 1942, when it was renamed the "Alpine and Danubian Gaue" (Alpen-und Donau-Reichsgaue).
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] In the Reichsgau, besides the main camp KZ-Mauthausen, there were numerous sub-camps in all provinces where Jews and other prisoners were killed, tortured and exploited.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] At this time, because the territory was outside the operational radius of Allied aircraft, the armaments industry was greatly expanded through the forced labour of concentration camp prisoners, this was especially the case with regard to the manufacture of fighter planes, tanks and missiles.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Most of the resistance groups were soon crushed by the Gestapo.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] While the plans of the group around Karl Burian to blow up the Gestapo's headquarters in Vienna were uncovered, the important group around the later executed priest Heinrich Maier managed to contact the Allies.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] This resistance group, which was in contact with the American secret service (OSS), soon provided information about mass executions and concentration camps such as Auschwitz.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The group's aim was to cause Nazi Germany to lose the war as quickly as possible and re-establish an independent Austria.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Vienna fell on 13 April 1945, during the Soviet Vienna offensive, just before the total collapse of the Third Reich.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The invading Allied powers, in particular the Americans, planned for the supposed "Alpine Fortress Operation" of a national redoubt, that was largely to have taken place on Austrian soil in the mountains of the Eastern Alps.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] However, it never materialised because of the rapid collapse of the Reich.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] (The date is officially named the birthday of the second republic.) At the end of April, most of western and southern Austria were still under Nazi rule.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] On 1 May 1945, the Federal Constitutional Law of 1920, which had been terminated by dictator Dollfuss on 1 May 1934, was declared valid again.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The total number of Austrian military deaths from 1939 to 1945 was 260,000.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The total number of Jewish Austrian Holocaust victims was 65,000.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] About 140,000 Jewish Austrians had fled from the country in 1938–39.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Thousands of Austrians had taken part in serious Nazi crimes (hundreds of thousands of people died in the Mauthausen-Gusen concentration camp alone), a fact which was officially acknowledged by Chancellor Franz Vranitzky in 1992.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Allied-occupied Austria was after World War II divided into military occupation zones.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Austria was governed by the Allied Commission for Austria.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] As stipulated in the Moscow Declaration of 1943 a subtle difference was seen in the treatment of Austria by the Allies.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The Austrian government, consisting of Social Democrats, Conservatives, and Communists resided in Vienna, which was surrounded by the Soviet zone.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] This Austrian government was recognised by the allies of World War II in October 1945 despite concerns that Karl Renner could be Stalin's puppet.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] On 26 July 1946 the Austrian Parliament passed its first nationalization law and approximately 70 mining and manufacturing companies were seized by the Austrian state.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The Ministry of Property Protection and Economic Planning (*Ministerium für Vermögenssicherung und Wirtschaftsplanung*) was responsible for directing the nationalized industries under the directorship of Minister Peter Krauland (party ÖVP).
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] On 15 May 1955, after talks which lasted for years and were influenced by the Cold War Austria regained full independence by concluding the Austrian State Treaty with the allies of World War II.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] On 26 October 1955, all occupation troops had left and Austria declared its *permanent neutrality* by an act of parliament.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] This day is now Austria's National Day, a public holiday.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The status of Tyrol was a lingering problem between Austria and Italy.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] To this day, there are 20 different squares in Austrian cities called "Südtiroler Platz" (South Tyrolean Square) in memory of the supposed loss of the Austrian territories.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Terrorist acts by the South Tyrolean independence movement have been documented in the 1950s and 1960s.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] A great degree of autonomy was granted to Tyrol by the Italian national government.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The political system of the Second Republic is based on the constitution of 1920 and 1929, which was reintroduced in 1945.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The system came to be characterised by *Proporz*, whereby most posts of political importance were split proportionately between members of the Social Democratic Party of Austria (SPÖ) and the Austrian People's Party (ÖVP).
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Interest group "chambers" with mandatory membership (e.g. for workers, business people, farmers) grew to considerable importance and were usually consulted in the legislative process, so hardly any legislation was passed that did not reflect widespread consensus.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Since 1945, governing via a single-party government has occurred twice: 1966–1970 (ÖVP) and 1970–1983 (SPÖ).
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] During all other legislative periods, either a grand coalition of SPÖ and ÖVP or a "small coalition" (one of these two and a smaller party) ruled the country.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Kurt Waldheim, the former secretary-general of the United Nations, was elected President of Austria from 1986 to 1992.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] He had been a Wehrmacht officer in the Second World War and was accused of war crimes.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Following a referendum in 1994, at which consent reached a majority of two-thirds, the country became a member of the European Union on 1 January 1995.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] In reality, Austria is taking part in the EU's Common Foreign and Security Policy, participates in peacekeeping and peace creating tasks, and has become a member of NATO's "Partnership for Peace"; the constitution has been amended accordingly.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Since Liechtenstein joined the Schengen Area in 2011, none of Austria's neighbouring countries performs border controls towards it anymore.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Austria is a largely mountainous country because of its location in the Alps.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The Central Eastern Alps, Northern Limestone Alps, and Southern Limestone Alps are all partly in Austria.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Of the total area of Austria (83,871 km2 or 32,383 sq mi), only about a quarter can be considered low-lying, and only 32% of the country is below 500 metres (1,640 ft).
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The Alps of western Austria give way somewhat into low lands and plains in the eastern part of the country.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Austria lies between latitudes 46° and 49° N, and longitudes 9° and 18° E.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] It can be divided into five areas, the biggest being the Eastern Alps, which constitute 62% of the nation's total area.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The Austrian foothills at the base of the Alps and the Carpathians account for about 12% and the foothills in the east and areas surrounding the periphery of the Pannoni low country amount to about 12% of the total landmass.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The second greater mountain area (much lower than the Alps) is situated in the north.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Known as the Austrian granite plateau, it is located in the central area of the Bohemian Mass and accounts for 10% of Austria.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The Austrian portion of the Vienna basin makes up the remaining 4%.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] In Austria, forest cover is about 47% of the total land area, equivalent to 3,899,150 hectares (ha) of forest in 2020, up from 3,775,670 hectares (ha) in 1990.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] In 2020, naturally regenerating forest covered 2,227,500 hectares (ha) and planted forest covered 1,671,500 hectares (ha).
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Of the naturally regenerating forest 2% was reported to be primary forest (consisting of native tree species with no clearly visible indications of human activity) and about 23% of the forest area was found within protected areas.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] For the year 2015, 18% of the forest area was reported to be under public ownership, 82% private ownership and 0% with ownership listed as other or unknown.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Phytogeographically, Austria belongs to the Central European province of the Circumboreal Region within the Boreal Kingdom.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] According to the WWF, the territory of Austria can be subdivided into four ecoregions: the Central European mixed forests, Pannonian mixed forests, Alps conifer and mixed forests, and Western European broadleaf forests.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Austria had a 2018 Forest Landscape Integrity Index mean score of 3.55/10, ranking it 149th globally out of 172 countries.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The greater part of Austria lies in the cool/temperate climate zone, where humid westerly winds predominate.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] With nearly three-quarters of the country dominated by the Alps, the alpine climate is predominant.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] In the east—in the Pannonian Plain and along the Danube valley—the climate shows continental features with less rain than the alpine areas.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Although Austria is cold in the winter (−10 to 0 °C), summer temperatures can be relatively high, with average temperatures in the mid-20s and a highest temperature of 40.5 °C (105 °F) in August 2013.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] According to the Köppen climate classification Austria has the following climate types: humid subtropical (Cfa), oceanic (Cfb), cool/warm-summer humid continental (Dfb), subarctic/subalpine (Dfc), tundra/alpine (ET), and ice-cap (EF).
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Austria may experience very cold, severe winters, but most of the time they are only around as cold as those in somewhat comparable climate zones, for example, Southern Scandinavia or Eastern Europe.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] As well, at higher altitudes, summers are usually considerably cooler than in the valleys/lower altitudes.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The subarctic and tundra climates seen around the Alps are much warmer in winter than what is normal elsewhere due in part to the Oceanic influence on this part of Europe.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Climate change in Austria has already caused temperature rises of almost 2 °C since 1880, and temperatures are expected to increase further while heat waves become more common.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Extreme precipitation events have become more frequent, and associated floods and landslides could threaten Austria's electricity supply security.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Austria's mountainous regions are highly sensitive to climate change and are experiencing reduced snowfall, earlier snowmelt and glacier loss.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The Parliament of Austria is located in Vienna, the country's capital and most populous city.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Austria became a federal, representative democratic republic through the Federal Constitutional Law of 1920.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The political system of the Second Republic with its nine states is based on the constitution of 1920, amended in 1929, which was re-enacted on 1 May 1945.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The president of Austria is the head of state.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The president is directly elected by popular majority vote, with a run-off between the top-scoring candidates if necessary.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The chancellor of Austria is head of the government.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The chancellor is selected by the president and tasked with forming a government based on the partisan composition of the lower house of parliament.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The government can be removed from office by either a presidential decree or by vote of no confidence in the lower chamber of parliament, the *Nationalrat*.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Voting for the president and for the parliament used to be compulsory in Austria.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The compulsion was abolished in steps from 1982 to 2004.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Austria's parliament consists of two chambers.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The voting age was lowered from 18 to 16 in 2007.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] While there is a general threshold of 4% of the vote for all parties in federal elections (*Nationalratswahlen*) to participate in the proportional allocation of seats, there remains the possibility of being elected to a seat directly in one of the 43 regional electoral districts (*Direktmandat*).
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The Nationalrat is the dominant chamber in the legislative process in Austria.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] However, the upper house of parliament, the *Bundesrat*, has a limited right of veto (the Nationalrat can—in almost all cases—ultimately pass the respective bill by voting a second time; this is referred to as a *Beharrungsbeschluss*, lit.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] A constitutional convention, called the *Österreich -Konvent* was convened on 30 June 2003 to consider reforms to the constitution, but failed to produce a proposal that would command a two-thirds majority in the Nationalrat, the margin necessary for constitutional amendments or reforms.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] While the bicameral Parliament and the Government constitute the legislative and executive branches, respectively, the courts are the third branch of Austrian state powers.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The Constitutional Court exerts considerable influence on the political system because of its power to invalidate legislation and ordinances that are not in compliance with the Constitution.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Since 1995, the European Court of Justice may overrule Austrian decisions in all matters defined in the laws of the European Union.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Austria also implements the decisions of the European Court of Human Rights, since the European Convention on Human Rights is part of the Austrian constitution.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] After the general election held in October 2006, the Social Democratic Party (SPÖ) emerged as the strongest party, and the Austrian People's Party (ÖVP) came in second, having lost about 8 Percentage points of its previous polling.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Political realities prohibited any of the two major parties from forming a coalition with smaller parties.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] In January 2007 the ÖVP and SPÖ formed a grand coalition with Alfred Gusenbauer (SPÖ) as Chancellor.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The election in September 2008 further weakened both major parties (SPÖ 29.3 % and ÖVP 26.0 %).
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] They formed a coalition with Werner Faymann (SPÖ) as Chancellor (First Faymann government).
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The Green Party came in third with 11% of the vote.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The FPÖ and the deceased Jörg Haider's new party Alliance for the Future of Austria, both on the political right, were strengthened during the election but taken together received less than 20% of the vote.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] On 11 October 2008, Jörg Haider died in a car accident.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] In the legislative elections of 2013, the Social Democratic Party received 27% of the vote and 52 seats; the People's Party 24% and 47 seats, thus controlling together the majority of the seats.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The Freedom Party received 40 seats and 21% of the votes, while the Greens received 12% and 24 seats.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Two new parties, Stronach and the NEOS, received less than 10% of the vote, and 11 and nine seats respectively.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] On 17 May 2016, Christian Kern from Social Democrats (SPÖ) was sworn in as the new chancellor.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] He continued governing in a "grand coalition" with the conservative People's Party (ÖVP).
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] He took the office after the former chancellor, also from SPÖ, Werner Faymann's resignation.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] On 26 January 2017, Alexander Van der Bellen was sworn in as the mostly ceremonial – but symbolically significant – role of Austrian president.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] After the Grand Coalition broke in Spring 2017 a snap election was proclaimed for October 2017.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The Austrian People's Party (ÖVP) with its new young leader Sebastian Kurz emerged as the largest party in the National Council, winning 31.5% of votes and 62 of the 183 seats.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The Social Democratic Party (SPÖ) finished second with 52 seats and 26.9% votes, slightly ahead of the Freedom Party of Austria (FPÖ), which received 51 seats and 26 percent.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The ÖVP decided to form a coalition with the FPÖ.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The new government between the centre-right wing and the right-wing populist party under the new chancellor Sebastian Kurz was sworn in on 18 December 2017, but the coalition government later collapsed in the wake of the "Ibiza" corruption scandal and new elections were called for 29 September 2019.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The elections led to another landslide victory (37.5 percent) of the Austrian People's Party (ÖVP) which formed a coalition government with the reinvigorated (13.9 percent) Greens, which was sworn in with Kurz as chancellor on 7 January 2020.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] On 11 October 2021, Chancellor Sebastian Kurz resigned following pressure from a corruption scandal.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] He was succeeded by Foreign Minister Alexander Schallenberg of the ÖVP.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] However, Schallenberg stepped down after less than two months, and Karl Nehammer was sworn in as chancellor on 6 December 2021, making him Austria's third conservative leader in two months.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The ÖVP and the Greens continued to govern together.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Following the election on 29 September 2024, coalition negotiations between the ÖVP, SPÖ, and NEOS collapsed, leading to Nehammer's resignation.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Schallenberg stepped in as interim chancellor for the second time.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Attempts to form an ÖVP-FPÖ coalition also failed.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Eventually, the ÖVP, SPÖ, and NEOS reached an agreement, forming a coalition government with Christian Stocker (ÖVP) as chancellor (Stocker government).
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Austria is a federal republic consisting of nine states (Austrian German: *Bundesländer*).
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The states are sub-divided into districts (*Bezirke*) and statutory cities (*Statutarstädte*).
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Districts are subdivided into municipalities (*Gemeinden*).
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Statutory Cities have the competencies otherwise granted to both districts and municipalities.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Vienna is unique in that it is both a city and a state.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The European Commission's Directorate-General for Translation calls the states *provinces*.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The 1955 Austrian State Treaty ended the occupation of Austria following World War II and recognised Austria as an independent and sovereign state.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] On 26 October 1955, the Federal Assembly passed a constitutional article in which "Austria declares of her own free will her perpetual neutrality".
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The second section of this law stated that "in all future times Austria will not join any military alliances and will not permit the establishment of any foreign military bases on her territory".
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Since then, Austria has shaped its foreign policy on the basis of neutrality, but rather different from the neutrality of Switzerland.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Austria began to reassess its definition of neutrality following the fall of the Soviet Union, granting overflight rights for the UN-sanctioned action against Iraq in 1991, and since 1995, it has developed participation in the EU's Common Foreign and Security Policy.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Also in 1995, it joined NATO's Partnership for Peace (although it was careful to do so only after Russia joined) and subsequently participated in peacekeeping missions in Bosnia.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Meanwhile, the only part of the Constitutional Law on Neutrality of 1955 still fully valid is not to allow foreign military bases in Austria.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Austria signed the UN's Nuclear Weapon Ban Treaty, which was opposed by all NATO members.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The manpower of the Austrian Armed Forces (Austrian German: *Bundesheer*) mainly relies on conscription.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] All males who have reached the age of eighteen and are found fit have to serve a six months compulsory military service, followed by an eight-year reserve obligation.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Both males and females at the age of sixteen are eligible for voluntary service.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Conscientious objection is legally acceptable and those who claim this right are obliged to serve an institutionalised nine months civilian service instead.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Since 1998, women volunteers have been allowed to become professional soldiers.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Austria is a landlocked country and has no navy.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] In 2012, Austria's defence expenditures corresponded to approximately 0.8% of its GDP.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The Army currently has about 26,000 soldiers, of whom about 12,000 are conscripts.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] As head of state, the Austrian president is nominally the commander-in-chief of the Armed Forces.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Command of the Austrian Armed Forces is exercised by the minister of defence, as of May 2020: Klaudia Tanner.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] This assistance came to an end when Hungary and Slovakia joined the EU Schengen Area in 2008, for all intents and purposes abolishing "internal" border controls between treaty states.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Some politicians have called for a prolongation of this mission, but the legality of this is heavily disputed.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] In accordance with the Austrian constitution, armed forces may only be deployed in a limited number of cases, mainly to defend the country and aid in cases of national emergency, such as in the wake of natural disasters.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] They may only exceptionally be used as auxiliary police forces.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Within its self-declared status of permanent neutrality, Austria has a tradition of engaging in UN-led peacekeeping and other humanitarian missions.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] The Austrian Forces Disaster Relief Unit (AFDRU), in particular, an all-volunteer unit with close ties to civilian specialists (e.g. rescue dog handlers) enjoys a reputation as a quick (standard deployment time is 10 hours) and efficient SAR unit.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] Currently, larger contingents of Austrian forces are deployed in Bosnia and Kosovo.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p01] According to the 2024 Global Peace Index, Austria is the 3rd most peaceful country in the world.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Austria consistently ranks high in terms of GDP per capita, due to its highly industrialised economy, and well-developed social market economy.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Until the 1980s, many of Austria's largest industry firms were nationalised; in recent years, however, privatisation has reduced state holdings to a level comparable to other European economies.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Labour movements are particularly influential, exercising a large influence on labour politics and decisions related to the expansion of the economy.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Next to a highly developed industry, international tourism is the most important part of the economy of Austria.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Germany has historically been the main trading partner of Austria, making it vulnerable to rapid changes in the German economy.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Since Austria became a member state of the European Union, it has gained closer ties to other EU economies.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Membership of the EU has drawn an influx of foreign investors attracted by Austria's access to the single European market and proximity to the aspiring economies of the European Union.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] At least 67% of Austria's imports come from other European Union member states.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] The 2008 financial crisis led to the Hypo Alpe-Adria-Bank International to be purchased in December 2009 by the government for 1 euro owing to credit difficulties, thus wiping out the €1.63bn of BayernLB.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] As of February 2014, the HGAA situation was unresolved, causing Chancellor Werner Faymann to warn that its failure would be comparable to the 1931 Creditanstalt event.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Austria indicated on 16 November 2010 that it would withhold the December instalment of its contribution to the EU bailout of Greece, citing the material worsening of the Greek debt situation and the apparent inability of Greece to collect the level of tax receipts it had previously promised.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Since the fall of communism, Austrian companies have been quite active players and consolidators in Eastern Europe.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Between 1995 and 2010, 4,868 mergers and acquisitions with a total known value of 163 billion EUR with the involvement of Austrian firms have been announced.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Tourism in Austria accounts for almost 9% of its gross domestic product.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] In 2007, Austria ranked 9th worldwide in international tourism receipts, with 18.9 billion US$.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] In international tourist arrivals, Austria ranked 12th with 20.8 million tourists.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] In 1972 the country began construction of a nuclear power plant to produce electricity at Zwentendorf on the River Danube, following a unanimous vote in parliament.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] However, in 1978 a referendum voted approximately 50.5% against nuclear power, 49.5% for, and parliament subsequently unanimously passed a law forbidding the use of nuclear power to generate electricity although the nuclear power plant had already finished.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Austria currently produces more than half of its electricity by hydropower.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Together with other renewable energy sources such as wind power, solar power, and biomass, the electricity supply from renewable energy amounts to 62.89 percent.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Compared to most European countries, Austria is ecologically well endowed.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Its biocapacity (or biological natural capital) is more than double of the world average: In 2016 Austria had 3.8 global hectares of biocapacity per person within its territory, compared to the world average of 1.6 global hectares per person.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] By contrast, in 2016 they used 6.0 global hectares of biocapacity which amounts to Austria's ecological footprint of consumption.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] This means that Austrians use about 60% more biocapacity than Austria contains.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] As a result, Austria is running a biocapacity deficit.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Rail transport in Austria is primarily provided by the national carrier Austrian Federal Railways (*Österreichische Bundesbahnen*, ÖBB).
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] It operates most commuter rail systems and long-distance trains.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Austria's population was estimated to be 9,220,882 in April 2026 by Statistik Austria.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] The population of the capital, Vienna, exceeds 2 million, representing about a quarter of the country's population.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] It is known for its cultural offerings and high standard of living.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] All other cities have fewer than 100,000 inhabitants.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] According to Statistik Austria, at the beginning of 2024, there were 1.8 million foreign-born residents in Austria, corresponding to 22.3% of the total population.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] There are more than 620,100 descendants of foreign-born immigrants.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] There are a group of legally recognized indigenous non-German speaking minorities, like Carinthian Slovenes, or the approximately 25,000 Romani people.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] The total fertility rate (TFR) in 2023 was estimated at 1.32 children born per woman, below the replacement rate of 2.1, it remains considerably below the high of 4.83 children born per woman in 1873.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] In 2015, 42.1% of births were to unmarried women.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Austria had the 14th oldest population in the world in 2020, with the average age of 44.5 years.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] The life expectancy in 2024 was estimated at 82.3 years, placing Austria above the EU average of 81.7 years.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] In 2024, Statistik Austria estimated that the population will grow to 10,179,834 people by 2080, primarily driven by immigration.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] The official language of Austria is German, as specified by article 8 of its constitution of 1920.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] The written form of German in Austria and in the Italian South Tyrol region is Austrian German, or simply Austrian, a variety of Standard High German; it has been standardized in Austria since 1951, when the Ministry of Education, Science and Research published the *Österreichisches Wörterbuch*.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] This standard form, however, is used primarily in education and for government publications, announcements and websites; the *de facto* common spoken languages of Austria are not the Austrian German as taught in schools but rather the Bavarian and Alemannic dialects.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] These are two mutually intelligible Upper German local languages or collections of dialects that are understood, with varying degrees of difficulty, by each other as well as by speakers of non-Austrian German dialects.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] The Austrian state of Carinthia is home to a significant indigenous Slovene-speaking minority, while in the easternmost state, Burgenland (formerly part of the Hungarian portion of Austria-Hungary), there are significant Hungarian- and Croatian-speaking minorities.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Burgenland Croatian, Hungarian, and Slovene are also recognized as official languages beside German in parts of Carinthia and Burgenland.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] According to census information published by Statistik Austria, there were a total of 710,926 foreign nationals living in Austria in 2001.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Of these, the largest by far were 283,334 foreign nationals from the former Yugoslavia (of whom 135,336 spoke Serbian; 105,487 Croatian; 31,591 Bosnian — i.e., 272,414 Austrian resident native speakers in total, plus 6,902 Slovenian and 4,018 Macedonian speakers).
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] The predominant historic ethnicity of Austrians is German speaking, which is closely related to people from neighbouring countries Germany, Liechtenstein, and German-speaking Switzerland.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Austrian ethnicity has considerable convergence with non-German speaking populations to the east and south of Austria, particularly in Vienna, through its position and role in Eastern Europe today and as the capital of the former multi-ethnic Habsburg Empire.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] This is reflected in the officially recognized non-German speaking indigneous populations of Austria.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] An estimated 13,000 to 40,000 Slovenes in the Austrian state Carinthia (the Carinthian Slovenes) as well as Croats (about 30,000) and Hungarians in Burgenland were recognised as a minority and have had special rights following the Austrian State Treaty (*Staatsvertrag*) of 1955.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Since 1994 the Romani people and Sinti have been an officially recognised ethnic minority in Austria.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Austria's people who are of non-Austrian descent, many come from surrounding countries, especially from the former East Bloc nations.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Guest workers *(Gastarbeiter)* and their descendants, as well as refugees from the Yugoslav wars and other conflicts, also form an important minority group in Austria.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] The largest single immigrant group in Austria are Germans, only collectively surpassed by people from ex-Jugoslavian countries.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] The largest group of people born in ex-Jugoslavian countries are from Bosnia and Herzegovina.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] The next biggest group are people born in Turkey.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] People from Turkey are closely followed by people from Serbia.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Serbs form one of the largest ethnic groups in Austria, numbering around 300,000 people.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Historically, Serbian immigrants moved to Austria during the time of the Austro-Hungarian Empire, when Vojvodina was under Imperial control.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Following World War II the number of Serbs expanded again, and today the community is very large.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] The Austrian Serbian Society was founded in 1936.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Today, Serbs in Austria are mainly found in Vienna, Salzburg, and Graz.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Austria was historically a strongly Catholic country as the centre of the Habsburg monarchy, which championed Catholicism.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] In 2001, about 74% of Austria's population were registered as Catholic, while about 5% considered themselves Protestants.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Austrian Christians, both Catholic and Protestant, are obliged to pay a mandatory membership fee (calculated by income – about 1%) to their churches; this payment is called the *Kirchenbeitrag* ("ecclesiastical contribution").
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] From the second half of the 20th century, the number of adherents and churchgoers has declined.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Data for 2023 list 4,638,000 members of the Catholic Church, or about 50% of the total Austrian population, yet Sunday church attendance was only 347,000, or 3.7% of the total Austrian population.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Additionally, the Lutheran church recorded a loss of 74,421 adherents between 2001 and 2016.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] The 2001 census reported that about 12% of the population declared themselves without a religion; according to ecclesiastical information, this share had grown to 20% by 2015 and further increased to 22.4% (1,997,700 people) in 2021.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Of the remaining population, about 340,000 were registered as members of various Muslim communities in 2001, originating chiefly from Turkey, Bosnia-Herzegovina, and Kosovo; the number of Muslims doubled in the fifteen years to 2016, to 700,000, and reached 745,600 in 2021.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] In 2021, another 436,700 residents of Austria (mostly Serbs) were members of Eastern Orthodox Churches, 26,600 were Buddhists, 10,100 were Hindus, about 21,800 were active Jehovah's Witnesses, and 5,400 were Jews.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Education in Austria is federally governed by the Ministry of Education, Science and Research, with administration handled by individual states.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] School attendance is mandatory for nine years, typically from ages six to fifteen.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Kindergarten is available for children aged three to six, with compulsory attendance starting at five.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] While part-time daycare is free nationwide for this age group, Vienna and Burgenland offer free all-day care.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] By 2018, about 90% of children between three and five attended early childhood education.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Volksschule or Grundschule starts at age six and lasts for four years, with an average class size of 18 pupils.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Secondary education is divided into different tracks: Mittelschule, which focuses on vocational training, and Allgemeinbildende Höhere Schule, an academic secondary school that prepares students for university through the Matura examination.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] At age 10, students, parents, and teachers decide the most suitable path based on the child's abilities and interests.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Austria is also known for its dual education system, which integrates theoretical learning with practical training; in 2021, 34.1% of secondary level II students participated in this system.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Austria allocated 4.9% of its GDP to education in 2021, with spending per student averaging US$16,734.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] German proficiency is essential in public schools, and children's language skills are assessed using the MIKA-D test upon admission.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Students who require additional support receive targeted language assistance to facilitate integration into the educational system.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Even though Austria has a 0.9 health index and a life expectancy of 81 years, the country still faces numerous problems when it comes to health, one example being that 2 in 5 Austrians have a chronic condition.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] One of the most costly health services in the EU is located in Austria.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] In 2019, health spending per capita ranked third in the EU.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Health-related out-of-pocket expenditures are higher than the EU average.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] With 5.2 physicians per 1,000 inhabitants, Austria has among the highest physician density in OECD countries.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Overall, the country has 271 hospitals with a total of 45,596 physicians (data from 2017), about 54% of which work (also or primarily) in hospitals.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Although Austria has the second highest physician rate in the EU, a large share of physicians is tropical to retirement age (55 years and older), and may thus be at a higher risk of developing severe conditions in a specimen of COVID-19 infection.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] The number of nurses in Austria has been subject to debate in recent years with regard to definitions of qualifications and their interpretation in cross-country comparisons.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] A new mandatory health professional registry was set up in 2018.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] However, due to the elapsing of the COVID-19 pandemic in early 2020, compulsory registration has been suspended.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] This implies that professional activities in long-term superintendency are moreover possible without registration until the end of the pandemic by late spring 2022 (Transition without the pandemic is still to be defined).
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Austria's past as a European power and its cultural environment generated a broad contribution to various forms of art, most notably among them music.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Austria was the birthplace of many famous composers such as Joseph Haydn, Michael Haydn, Franz Liszt, Franz Schubert, Anton Bruckner, Johann Strauss Sr., and Johann Strauss Jr., as well as members of the Second Viennese School such as Arnold Schoenberg, Anton Webern, and Alban Berg.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart was born in Salzburg, then an independent Church Principality of the Holy Roman Empire, which later became part of Austria, and much of Mozart's career was spent in Vienna.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Vienna was for a long time an important centre of musical innovation.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] 18th- and 19th-century composers were drawn to the city due to the patronage of the Habsburgs, and made Vienna the European capital of classical music.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] During the Baroque period, Slavic and Hungarian folk forms influenced Austrian music.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Vienna's status began its rise as a cultural centre in the early 16th century and was focused around instruments, including the lute.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Ludwig van Beethoven spent the better part of his life in Vienna.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Austria's current national anthem, attributed to Mozart, was chosen after World War II to replace the traditional Austrian anthem by Joseph Haydn.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Austrian Herbert von Karajan was principal conductor of the Berlin Philharmonic for 35 years.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] He is generally regarded as one of the greatest conductors of the 20th century, and he was a dominant figure in European classical music from the 1960s until his death.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Austria was the cradle of numerous scientists with international reputation.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Among them are Ludwig Boltzmann, Ernst Mach, Victor Franz Hess, and Christian Doppler, prominent scientists in the 19th century.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] In the 20th century, contributions by Lise Meitner, Erwin Schrödinger, and Wolfgang Pauli to nuclear research and quantum mechanics were key to these areas' development during the 1920s and 1930s.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Prominent present-day quantum physicists are Anton Zeilinger and Peter Zoller renown for important developments in quantum optics and quantum information.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] In addition to physicists, Austria was the birthplace of two of the most noteworthy philosophers of the 20th century, Ludwig Wittgenstein and Karl Popper.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] In addition to them, biologists Gregor Mendel and Konrad Lorenz as well as mathematician Kurt Gödel and engineers such as Ferdinand Porsche and Siegfried Marcus were Austrians.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Bertha von Suttner became the first woman to be awarded the Nobel Peace Prize, and the first Austrian laureate.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] A focus of Austrian science has always been medicine and psychology, starting in medieval times with Paracelsus.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Eminent physicians like Theodore Billroth, Clemens von Pirquet, and Anton von Eiselsberg have built upon the achievements of the 19th-century Vienna School of Medicine.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Austria was home to Sigmund Freud, founder of psychoanalysis, Alfred Adler, founder of Individual psychology, psychologists Paul Watzlawick and Hans Asperger, and psychiatrist Viktor Frankl.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Austria was ranked 17th in the Global Innovation Index in 2024, but it declined to the 19th rank according to GII 2025.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] The Austrian School of Economics, which is prominent as one of the main competitive directions for economic theory, is related to Austrian economists Carl Menger, Joseph Schumpeter, Eugen von Böhm-Bawerk, Ludwig von Mises, and Friedrich Hayek.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Other noteworthy Austrian-born émigrés include the econimic anthropologist Karl Paul Polanyi, management thinker Peter Drucker, sociologist Paul Felix Lazarsfeld, and scientist Sir Gustav Nossal.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Austria's cuisine is derived from that of the Austro-Hungarian Empire.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Austrian cuisine is rooted in the long-standing traditions of the imperial court kitchen ("Hofküche"), which evolved over centuries within the Habsburg monarchy.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] It is distinguished by its refined and well-balanced preparation of beef and pork, as well as by a wide variety of vegetable-based dishes.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] In addition to native regional traditions, the cuisine has been influenced by Hungarian, Czech, Polish, Jewish, Italian, Balkan, and French cuisines, from which both dishes and methods of food preparation have often been borrowed.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] The Austrian cuisine is therefore one of the most multicultural and transcultural in Europe.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Typical Austrian dishes include Wiener Schnitzel, Schweinsbraten, Kaiserschmarren, Knödel, Sachertorte, and Tafelspitz.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] There are also Kärntner Kasnudeln, which are pockets of dough filled with Topfen, potatoes, herbs and peppermint which are boiled and served with a butter sauce.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Kasnudeln are traditionally served with a salad.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] The sugar block dispenser Pez was invented in Austria, as well as Mannerschnitten.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Austria is also famous for its Mozartkugeln and its coffee tradition.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] With over 8 kg per year it has the sixth highest per capita coffee consumption worldwide.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Beer is sold in 0.2-litre (a *Pfiff*), 0.3-litre (a *Seidel*, *kleines Bier* or *Glas Bier*) and 0.5-litre (a *Krügerl* or *großes Bier* or *Halbe*) measures.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] At festivals one litre *Maß* and two-litre *Doppelmaß* in the Bavarian style are also dispensed.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] The most popular types of beer are lager (known as *Märzen* in Austria), naturally cloudy *Zwicklbier* and wheat beer.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] At holidays like Christmas and Easter bock beer is also available.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] The most important wine-producing areas are in Lower Austria, Burgenland, Styria, and Vienna.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] The Grüner Veltliner grape provides some of Austria's most notable white wines and Zweigelt is the most widely planted red wine grape.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] In Upper Austria, Lower Austria, Styria, and Carinthia, *Most*, a type of cider or perry, is widely produced.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] A Schnapps of typically up to 60% alcohol or fruit brandy is drunk, which in Austria is made from a variety of fruits, for example apricots and rowanberries.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] The produce of small private schnapps distilleries, of which there are about 20,000 in Austria, is known as *Selbstgebrannter* or *Hausbrand*.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Local soft drinks such as Almdudler are very popular around the country as an alternative to alcoholic beverages.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Another popular drink is the so-called "Spezi", a mix between Coca-Cola and the original formula of Orange Fanta or the more locally renowned Frucade.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Red Bull, the highest-selling energy drink in the world, was introduced by Dietrich Mateschitz, an Austrian entrepreneur.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Due to the mountainous terrain, alpine skiing is a prominent sport in Austria and is extremely valuable in the promotion and economic growth of the country.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Similar sports such as snowboarding or ski-jumping are also widely popular.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Bobsleigh, luge, and skeleton are also popular events with a permanent track located in Igls, which hosted bobsleigh and luge competitions for the 1964 and 1976 Winter Olympics held in Innsbruck.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] The first Winter Youth Olympics in 2012 were held in Innsbruck as well.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Football in Austria is governed by the Austrian Football Association.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Austria was among the most successful football playing nations on the European continent, placing 4th at the 1934 FIFA World Cup, 3rd at the 1954 FIFA World Cup and 7th at the 1978 FIFA World Cup.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] However, Austrian football has not been internationally successful since the mid 20th century.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Austria co-hosted the 2008 UEFA European Football Championship with Switzerland.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] The national Austrian football league is the Austrian Bundesliga, which includes teams such as record-champions SK Rapid Wien, FK Austria Wien, Red Bull Salzburg, and Sturm Graz.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Besides football, Austria also has professional national leagues for most major team sports, including the Austrian Hockey League for ice hockey, Österreichische Basketball Bundesliga for basketball and the Austrian Football League for American football.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Horseback riding is also popular; the famed Spanish Riding School of Vienna is located in Vienna.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Niki Lauda was a Formula One driver who was three times F1 World Champion, winning in 1975, 1977 and 1984.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] He is currently the only driver to have been champion for both Ferrari and McLaren, the sport's two most successful constructors.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Other known Austrian F1 drivers include Gerhard Berger and Jochen Rindt.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Austria also hosts F1 races (Austrian Grand Prix); now held at the Red Bull Ring, in the past also at the Österreichring and the Zeltweg Airfield.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Thomas Muster is a former tennis player and was one of the world's leading clay court players in the 1990s.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] He won the 1995 French Open and in 1996 was ranked number 1 in the ATP ranking.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] 2020 US Open winner Dominic Thiem is also another prominent tennis player having been as high as world number 3 and also been in the finals of the French Open and Australian Open.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austria-p02] Other well known Austrian tennis players include Horst Skoff and Jürgen Melzer.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austrian-standards-international] The first standard was published in 1921 on metric screw threads.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austrian-standards-international] In 1932, the committee's name was shortened to the *Österreichischer Normenausschuss* (Austrian Standards Committee).
[src:austrian-standards-international/austrian-standards-international] With the Austrian *Anschluss* to Nazi Germany in 1938, it became a branch office of the German *Deutsches Institut für Normung* (DIN) standards organization, but resumed operations in its own right after World War II, and was a founding ISO member in 1946.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austrian-standards-international] The 1954 Federal Act on Standardization recognized the activities of the committee, and the Act, as amended, serves as its legal basis.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austrian-standards-international] The Austrian Standards Committee's name was changed to *ON Österreichisches Normungsinstitut* in 1969.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austrian-standards-international] On 1 March 2006, the Institute published ON rule ONR 168000, used to calculate the monetary value of a brand.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austrian-standards-international] In 2018, the name was changed to Austrian Standards International.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austrian-standards-international] The Institute is located at Heinestrasse 38, 1020 Vienna.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austrian-standards-international] The acronym ÖNORM designates a national standard published by the Austrian Standards International and applicable to Austria alone.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austrian-standards-international] Austrian national standards have the acronym "ÖNORM" followed by one letter and a unique number.
[src:austrian-standards-international/austrian-standards-international] In the examples above, the letter "S" following "ÖNORM" indicates that these standards address topics not covered elsewhere (*Sonstige Normengebiete* in German).
[src:austrian-standards-international/badan-standardisasi-nasional] The **National Standardization Agency** of Indonesia (Indonesian: *Badan Standardisasi Nasional*; **BSN**) is the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) member body for Indonesia.
[src:austrian-standards-international/badan-standardisasi-nasional] BSN is a non-ministerial Indonesian government agency with the main task of carrying out governmental tasks in the field of standardization and conformity assessment in Indonesia.
[src:austrian-standards-international/badan-standardisasi-nasional] The agency is also responsible to develop and maintain the Indonesian National Standard.
[src:austrian-standards-international/badan-standardisasi-nasional] Actively involved in various International Organizations such as ISO, IEC, CAC, APEC, APLAC, ILAC, PAC, ASEAN, and so on.
[src:austrian-standards-international/badan-standardisasi-nasional] Active participation of BSN can be in the form of attending international standard formulation sessions in order to fight for the interests of Indonesia, as well as hosting the session / hosting.
[src:austrian-standards-international/badan-standardisasi-nasional] Encouraging the central government, regional governments, associations, industry, and universities to participate actively in developing and promoting SNI.
[src:austrian-standards-international/badan-standardisasi-nasional] The efforts of BSN to encourage stakeholders to jointly conduct standardization and conformity assessment activities, are formally formulated through the signing of the Cooperation Text (MOU).
[src:austrian-standards-international/badan-standardisasi-nasional] Conducting research and testing of SNI products in the market, of which the results can be inputs for relevant Ministries that have the capacity to be market supervisors.
[src:austrian-standards-international/badan-standardisasi-nasional] The research activities conducted by BSN can also be included for SNI development and maintenance activities.
[src:austrian-standards-international/badan-standardisasi-nasional] Organizing National Standards of Measurement Unit that enable metrological activities in Indonesia to be recognized by the world.
[src:austrian-standards-international/badan-standardisasi-nasional] Implementation of guidance and general administrative services in the fields of general planning, administration, organization and governance, staffing, finance, filing, coding, equipment and household.
[src:austrian-standards-international/badan-standardisasi-nasional] 5. organizing education and training in its fields.
[src:austrian-standards-international/badan-standardisasi-nasional] The establishment of BSN is closely related to the long history of standardization in Indonesia.
[src:austrian-standards-international/badan-standardisasi-nasional] The development and application of standards began during the Dutch and Japanese colonial periods and continued after Indonesia declared independence and became officially sovereign.
[src:austrian-standards-international/badan-standardisasi-nasional] Standardization was initially used to support colonial economic activities and ensure their smooth operation.
[src:austrian-standards-international/badan-standardisasi-nasional] Dutch engineers, who were mostly civil engineers, began to set standards for building materials, transportation equipment, and electrical installation standards, as well as requirements for external lines.
[src:austrian-standards-international/badan-standardisasi-nasional] During World War II and the Japanese occupation (1942-1945), formal standardization activities were halted.
[src:austrian-standards-international/badan-standardisasi-nasional] However, on August 17, 1945, Indonesia proclaimed its independence.
[src:austrian-standards-international/badan-standardisasi-nasional] The country immediately formed a government and planned for development to improve the standard of living and welfare of the people, with the goal of achieving equality with other countries.
[src:austrian-standards-international/badan-standardisasi-nasional] In 1951 the amendment to the "Raad Normalization" statute was formed and the Indonesian Normalization Fund Foundation (YDNI) was formed.
[src:austrian-standards-international/badan-standardisasi-nasional] In 1955 YDNI represented Indonesia as a member of the ISO international standards organization and in 1966 YDNI successfully represented Indonesia as a member of the International Electrotechnical Commission / IEC.
[src:austrian-standards-international/badan-standardisasi-nasional] It turns out that this law has not been able to be a means of managing overall standardization activities.
[src:austrian-standards-international/badan-standardisasi-nasional] The government began to place standardization as a strategic function in supporting national development.
[src:austrian-standards-international/badan-standardisasi-nasional] In 1973, the "National System Development for Standardization" program was established as a priority.
[src:austrian-standards-international/badan-standardisasi-nasional] In 1976, the National Standardization System Preparation Committee was formed.
[src:austrian-standards-international/badan-standardisasi-nasional] In 1984, with the Decree of the President of the Republic of Indonesia the National Standardization Board (DSN) was formed with the main task of establishing standardization policies, coordinating and fostering cooperation in the field of national standardization.
[src:austrian-standards-international/badan-standardisasi-nasional] The Chairperson of the National Standardization Board is held by the State Minister for Research and Technology, Prof.
[src:austrian-standards-international/badan-standardisasi-nasional] Through the struggle of the previous leadership, Alm.
[src:austrian-standards-international/badan-standardisasi-nasional] Herudi Kartowisastro, on March 27, 1997, the government dissolved the DSN which subsequently changed to the National Standardization Body.
[src:austrian-standards-international/badan-standardisasi-nasional] BSN itself is a Non-Ministry Government Institution (LPNK) that is given the task by the government to foster and coordinate all standardization and conformity assessment activities in Indonesia.
[src:austrian-standards-international/badan-standardisasi-nasional] The establishment of BSN was based on Presidential Decree No.
[src:austrian-standards-international/badan-standardisasi-nasional] 13 of 1997 perfected by Presidential Decree No.
[src:austrian-standards-international/badan-standardisasi-nasional] 166 of 2000 concerning Position, Duties, Functions, Authority, Organizational Structure and Work Procedures of Non-Departmental Government Institutions as amended several times, and the most recent by Presidential Decree No.
[src:austrian-standards-international/badan-standardisasi-nasional] 4 of 2018, concerning the National Standardization Agency.
[src:austrian-standards-international/badan-standardisasi-nasional] In order to enhance the development of the Indonesian National Standard (SNI), the government established Government Regulation No.
[src:austrian-standards-international/badan-standardisasi-nasional] 102 of 2000 concerning National Standardization.
[src:austrian-standards-international/badan-standardisasi-nasional] 20 of 2014 concerning Standardization and Conformity Assessment was stipulated.
[src:austrian-standards-international/badan-standardisasi-nasional] With the existence of this Law, the government will further strengthen the existence and role of BSN in the development process in Indonesia both in the context of physical development, efficient management of natural resources, and the development of highly competitive Indonesian people.
[src:austrian-standards-international/badan-standardisasi-nasional] Welcoming the era of globalization which demands high competitiveness, as well as the implementation of Law No.
[src:austrian-standards-international/badan-standardisasi-nasional] 20 of 2014, the BSN successfully reorganized itself to include a new structure namely the Deputy for the National Standard Measuring Unit (SNSU) in 2018.
[src:austrian-standards-international/badan-standardisasi-nasional] The chairman of BSN is under and directly responsible to the President of Indonesia.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] The origins of the Bangladesh Standards and Testing Institution (BSTI) can be traced back to the mid-20th century during the period of East Pakistan.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] In 1955, a regional branch of the Central Testing Laboratories (CTL) was established in Dhaka to assess the quality of imported and domestically produced goods.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] This was followed by the establishment of a regional office of the Pakistan Standards Institution in Dhaka in 1957, and the creation of the Certification Marks Inspectorate in Chittagong in 1963 to regulate industrial product certification.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] Following Bangladesh's independence in 1971, the Bangladesh Standards Institution (BDSI) was formed as the country's national standards body.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] It became a member of the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) in 1974.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] In an effort to consolidate standards development, testing, and certification functions, the government enacted Ordinance No.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] XXXVII of 1985, merging BDSI and CTL to form the present-day Bangladesh Standards and Testing Institution (BSTI).
[src:austrian-standards-international/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] The institution's scope was further expanded in 1995 with the merger of the Department of Agricultural Grading and Marking.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] Earlier, in 1982, the Standards of Weights and Measures Ordinance was promulgated to implement the metric system across the country, a function now overseen by BSTI.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] BSTI operates under the Ministry of Industries and serves as the national authority for standardization, conformity assessment, and metrology.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] Over the years, it has undergone significant modernization.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] A National Metrology Laboratory was established with financial and technical assistance from the European Union, NORAD, UNIDO, and the Government of Bangladesh.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] BSTI's laboratories—covering physical, chemical, and microbiological testing—have received accreditation from the National Accreditation Board for Testing and Calibration Laboratories (NABL) of India.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] Its product certification scheme is accredited by the National Accreditation Board for Certification Bodies (NABCB) of India.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] The Management System Certification (MSC) program has also been accredited by both Norwegian Accreditation and the Bangladesh Accreditation Board (BAB).
[src:austrian-standards-international/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] In recent years, BSTI expanded its infrastructure with the inauguration of a modern testing facility in Khulna on 21 November 2023, followed by the opening of a ten-story center in Chittagong's Agrabad Commercial Area on 28 June 2025.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] The Chittagong facility, equipped with advanced laboratories, aims to bolster the region's role as a major port and industrial hub by strengthening BSTI's capabilities in product testing, certification, and trade facilitation.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] The responsibility of promulgating these standards lies with the Bangladesh Standards and Testing Institution (BSTI), while the task of technical drafting and declaration is carried out by the BCC.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] The organization has already developed several standards and simultaneously modernized the existing ones.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] Due to lack of coherence and synergy between vendors and technologists, these standards were largely never widely accepted nor recognized by international bodies.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] Later, versions of standards such as BSCII in essence rubber stamped Unicode encoding scheme.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] An official order to mandatorily install a keyboard layout package kit in 2018 spawned furor over multiple fronts.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] BSTI is the national standards body of Bangladesh, responsible for formulating and issuing Bangladesh Standards (BDS) for products, services, and processes.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] Since its establishment, BSTI has developed over 4,000 standards to ensure quality, safety, and compliance.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] It certifies products that meet national standards by issuing a Certification Mark (CM) licence, valid for three years, following thorough factory inspections and laboratory testing.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] Use of the BSTI certification mark is restricted to licensed manufacturers.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] Currently, 315 products require mandatory CM licences for domestic production, distribution, and sale, while 79 imported items need BSTI clearance under the country's import policy.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] BSTI's Metrology Division regulates packaged commodities under the *Package Commodity Registration Rules 2021* and calibrates weighing and measuring devices to ensure adherence to the International System of Units.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] The institution also provides laboratory testing and calibration services to industries, markets, government offices, and individuals.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] Its monitoring activities include market surveillance, mobile courts, and random sampling from markets and factories to combat substandard or counterfeit goods.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] Additionally, BSTI represents Bangladesh in international and regional standards organizations and promotes public awareness of quality standards and consumer rights.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] BSTI is an autonomous agency of the Government of Bangladesh.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] It operates its activities under the *Bangladesh Standards & Testing Institution Act - 2018*.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] A counsel of 37 members is the decision-making body of the institution.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bangladesh-standards-and-testing-institution] Minister for the Ministry of Industries is the chairperson of the counsel.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bsi-group] The **British Standards Institution** (**BSI**) is the national standards body of the United Kingdom.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bsi-group] BSI produces technical standards on a wide range of products and services and also supplies standards certification services for business and personnel.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bsi-group] BSI was founded as the Engineering Standards Committee in London in 1901.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bsi-group] It subsequently extended its standardization work and became the British Engineering Standards Association in 1918, adopting the name British Standards Institution in 1931 after receiving a Royal Charter in 1929.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bsi-group] In 1998, a revision of the Charter enabled the organization to diversify and acquire other businesses, and the trading name was changed to BSI Group.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bsi-group] The Group now operates in 195 countries.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bsi-group] The core business remains standards and standards related services, although the majority of the Group's revenue comes from management systems assessment and certification work.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bsi-group] In 2021, BSI appointed its first female chief executive officer, Susan Taylor Martin.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bsi-group] BSI produces British Standards, and, as the UK's National Standards Body, is also responsible for the UK publication, in English, of international and European standards.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bsi-group] BSI is obliged to adopt and publish all European Standards as identical British Standards (prefixed BS EN) and to withdraw pre-existing British Standards that are in conflict.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bsi-group] However, it has the option to adopt and publish international standards (prefixed BS ISO or BS IEC).
[src:austrian-standards-international/bsi-group] In response to commercial demands, BSI also produces commissioned standards products such as Publicly Available Specifications (PASs), Private Standards and Business Information Publications.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bsi-group] These products are commissioned by individual organizations and trade associations to meet their needs for standardized specifications, guidelines, codes of practice etc.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bsi-group] Because they are not subject to the same consultation and consensus requirements as formal standards, the lead time is shorter.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bsi-group] BSI also publishes standards-related books, CD-ROMs, subscription and web-based products as well as providing training on standards-related issues.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bsi-group] With 80,000 clients, BSI is one of the world's largest certification bodies.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bsi-group] It audits and provides certification to companies worldwide who implement management systems standards.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bsi-group] BSI also runs training courses that cover the implementation and auditing requirements of national and international management systems standards.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bsi-group] BSI's best known product in the UK is the Kitemark, a registered certification mark first used in 1903.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bsi-group] The Kitemark – which is recognized by 82% of UK adults – signifies products or services which have been assessed and tested as meeting the requirements of the related specification or standard within a Kitemark scheme.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bsi-group] BSI also conducts testing of products for a range of certifications, including for CE marking.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bsi-group] CE marking must be applied to a wide range of products intended for sale in the European Economic Area.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bsi-group] Frequently, manufacturers or importers need a third-party certification of their product from an accredited or 'Notified' body.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bsi-group] BSI holds Notified Body status for 15 EU Directives, including construction products, marine equipment, pressurized equipment and personal protective equipment.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bsi-group] BSI also conducts testing for manufacturers developing new products and has facilities to test across a wide range of sectors, including construction, fire safety, electrical and electronic and engineering products.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bsi-group] BSI provides regulatory and quality management reviews and product certification for medical device manufacturers in the Worldwide.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bsi-group] It is the market leader in the US, the world's biggest healthcare market.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bsi-group] In 2021, BSI Group, with support from the Construction Products Association, led the development of a product identification and traceability system known as *BSI Identify*.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bsi-group] The initiative responded to recommendations made by Dame Judith Hackitt following her review of building safety, which called for wider adoption of permanent product marking and consistent labelling systems to improve traceability across the built environment sector.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bsi-group] BSI Identify uses new Digital Object Identifier (DOI) technology "to deliver a unique, constant, and interoperable identifier", known as a BSI UPIN, "which can be assigned to products to help UK manufacturers to directly manage information about their products in the supply chain".
[src:austrian-standards-international/bsi-group] The aim of the BSI Identify programme is that "wherever you are with [a] product, you can take a snapshot of the QR code with your mobile device, and it will immediately take you to the product technical data sheet.
[src:austrian-standards-international/bsi-group] The BSI coat of arms was granted by the College of Arms in 1951.
